/elections/support/ok_filing_2020.html</ref>\n\n==== Endorsements ====\n{{Endorsements box\n|title=Markwayne Mullin\n|list=\n;U.S. Presidents\n* [[Donald Trump]], [[President of the United States]]<ref>{{cite web| title=Trump went on a mini-endorsement spree on Tuesday| url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/morning-score/2019/12/18/the-impeachment-vote-whip-count-783830| publisher=Politico| date=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n====Primary Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Markwayne Mullin]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Joseph Silk (politician)|Joseph Silk]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Rhonda Hopkins\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n====Declared====\n*Danyell Lanier <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://danyell2020.com|title=Elect Danyell Lanier in the U.S. House of Representatives|website=danyell2020.com}}</ref>\n\n===Libertarian primary===\n====Candidates====\n====Declared====\n*Richie Castaldo, 2018 nominee <ref>https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_filing_2020.html</ref>\n\n===General election===\n====Polling====\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Oklahoma's 2nd congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = TBA\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Danyell Lanier\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Richie Castaldo\n| party = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 3==\n{{see also|Oklahoma's 3rd congressional district}}\nThe 3rd district is located in [[Western Oklahoma]]. The largest district in Oklahoma and one of the largest in the country, it includes the [[Oklahoma Panhandle]], [[Ponca City, Oklahoma|Ponca City]] and the city of [[Stillwater, Oklahoma|Stillwater]] as well as the [[Osage Nation]]. The incumbent is Republican [[Frank Lucas (Oklahoma politician)|Frank Lucas]], who has represented the district since 2003 and previously represented the 6th district from 1994 to 2003. He was re-elected with 74% of the vote in 2018.\n===Republican primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n*[[Frank Lucas (Oklahoma politician)|Frank D. Lucas]], incumbent U.S. Representative\n\n=====Withdrew=====\n*Joshua Jantz <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://joshuajantz.com|title=Joshua Jantz - Unleash Freedom|website=Joshua Jantz}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n====Declared====\n*Zoe Midyett <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.midyett2020.com/|title=Zoe Midyett is running for U.S. Congress in November 2020. District 3, Oklahoma|website=Mysite}}</ref>\n\n===General election===\n====Polling====\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Oklahoma's 3rd congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Frank D. Lucas\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate  = Zoe Midyett\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 4==\n{{see also|Oklahoma's 4th congressional district}}\nThe 4th district is located in [[South Central Oklahoma]] and includes the suburbs of Oklahoma City, such as the counties of  [[Canadian County, Oklahoma|Canadian]], [[Comanche County, Oklahoma|Comanche]] and [[Cleveland County, Oklahoma|Cleveland]] and numerous other sparsely populated counties. The incumbent is Republican [[Tom Cole]], who has represented the district since 2003. He was re-elected with 63% of the vote in 2018.\n\n===Republican primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n*James Taylor, teacher, runner-up in 2016 and 2018\n*[[Tom Cole]], incumbent U.S. Representative\n*Trevor Sipes\n*Gilbert O. Sanders <ref>https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_filing_2020.html</ref>\n\n====Primary Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Tom Cole]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = James Taylor\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Trevor Sipes\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Gilbert O. Sanders\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n====Declared====\n*Mary Brannon\n*John D. Argo\n*David R. Slemmons <ref>https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_filing_2020.html</ref>\n\n====Withdrew====\n*Wyndi Brown <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votewyndibrown.com/|title=Wyndi Brown for Congress \u2013 Oklahoma District 4}}</ref>\n*Wesley Forbes <ref>https://www.wesleyforbesforcongress.com/</ref>\n\