Oklahoma politician)|Frank D. Lucas]], incumbent U.S. Representative\n\n=====Withdrew=====\n*Joshua Jantz <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://joshuajantz.com|title=Joshua Jantz - Unleash Freedom|website=Joshua Jantz}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n====Declared====\n*Zoe Midyett <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.midyett2020.com/|title=Zoe Midyett is running for U.S. Congress in November 2020. District 3, Oklahoma|website=Mysite}}</ref>\n\n===General election===\n====Polling====\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Oklahoma's 3rd congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Frank D. Lucas\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n|candidate  = Zoe Midyett\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 4==\n{{see also|Oklahoma's 4th congressional district}}\nThe 4th district is located in [[South Central Oklahoma]] and includes the suburbs of Oklahoma City, such as the counties of  [[Canadian County, Oklahoma|Canadian]], [[Comanche County, Oklahoma|Comanche]] and [[Cleveland County, Oklahoma|Cleveland]] and numerous other sparsely populated counties. The incumbent is Republican [[Tom Cole]], who has represented the district since 2003. He was re-elected with 63% of the vote in 2018.\n\n===Republican primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n*James Taylor, teacher, runner-up in 2016 and 2018\n*[[Tom Cole]], incumbent U.S. Representative\n*Trevor Sipes\n*Gilbert O. Sanders <ref>https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_filing_2020.html</ref>\n\n====Primary Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Tom Cole]] (incumbent)\n| party = Re