ws|url=https://www.apnews.com/f26bfc52287b4a63af5e7740aaf460da|accessdate=October 2, 2019|work=[[Associated Press]]|date=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n*Charles Tuffy Pringle\n*David Hill, businessman<ref name=\"OK05GOP\"/>\n*[[Terry Neese]], entrepreneur and nominee for [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma|Lieutenant Governor]] in 1990<ref>{{cite news |last1=Felder |first1=Ben |title=Neese becomes second Republican to seek 5th District seat |url=https://newsok.com/article/5629741/neese-becomes-second-republican-to-seek-5th-district-seat |accessdate=April 25, 2019 |publisher=The Oklahoman |date=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n*Michael Ballard, veteran<ref>{{cite news |last1=Van Risseghem |first1=David |title=Neese & Ballard Join Race For Congress |url=https://www.soonerpolitics.org/editorial/neese-ballard-join-race-for-congress |accessdate=May 31, 2019 |publisher=Sooner Politics |date=April 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*Miles V. Rahimi, Navy Veteran and Community Organizer<ref>{{cite news|last1=Casteel |first=Chris |title=GOP Hopefuls Speak To Crowd Eager To Reclaim Congressional Seat |url=https://oklahoman.com/article//gop-hopefuls-speak-to-crowd-eager-to-reclaim-congressional-seat |accessdate=February 23, 2020 |publisher=The Oklahoman |date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n*Shelli Landon\n*[[Stephanie Bice]], Oklahoma State Senator <ref>{{Cite news|last1=Casteel|first1=Chris|title=Bice to challenge Horn for congressional seat|url=https://newsok.com/article/5629581/bice-to-challenge-horn-in-for-congressional-seat|newspaper=The Oklahoman|date=April 24, 2019|accessdate=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n*Jake A. Merrick <ref>https://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_filing_2020.html</ref>\n\n=====Withdrew=====\n*Dan Belcher<ref>http://danthemancongress.com</ref>\n*Merideth VanSant, businesswoman<ref>{{cite news |last1=Staff |first1=Edmond Sun |title=VanSant announces candidacy for 5th Congressional District|url=https://www.edmondsun.com/news/local_news/vansant-announces-candidacy-for-th-congressional-district/article_d60e6e5e-818c-11e9-ad82-0f182e1c4ea5.html |accessdate=June 7, 2019 |publisher=The Edmond Sun |date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n*David Greene<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.davidgreene.me/|title=Headquarters|website=Greene for Congress}}</ref>\n\n=====Declined=====\n*Kevin Calvey, [[Oklahoma County]] commissioner<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|last1=Riley|first1=Patrick|title=Kendra Horn\u2019s first challenger steps into the ring...|url=https://www.thelostogle.com/2019/04/25/kendra-horns-first-potential-challenger-steps-into-the-ring/|publisher=The Lost Ogle|date=April 25, 2019|accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bruno|first1=Jessica|title=War of words on display between sheriff, commissioner\n|url=https://kfor.com/2019/04/24/war-of-words-on-display-between-sheriff-commissioner/ |publisher= Oklahoma News 4|date=April 24, 2019|accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Mick Cornett]], former mayor of [[Oklahoma City]] and candidate for [[Governor of Oklahoma]] in [[2018 Oklahoma gubernatorial election#Republican primary|2018]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casteel |first1=Chris |title=Cornett won't seek congressional seat, sources say |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/5643573/cornett-wont-seek-congressional-seat-sources-say |website=The Oklahoman |accessdate=October 10, 2019 |date=October 10, 2019}}</ref>\n*Carol Hefner, Donald Trump\u2019s 2016 Oklahoma campaign manager<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*Bob Mills, businessman & co-chair for Donald Trump's 2016 Campaign in Oklahoma<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*[[Steve Russell (politician)|Steve Russell]], former U.S. Representative<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mutnick|first1=Ally|title=Inside the Midterms' Biggest House Upset|url=https://www.nationaljournal.com/s/674872/inside-the-midterms-biggest-house-upset|publisher=National Journal|date=November 26, 2018|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Greg Treat]], president pro tempore of the [[Oklahoma Senate]]<ref name=\"OK05Hermes\">{{cite news|last1=Hermes|first1=Grant|title=Rep. Horn Being Targeted In 2020 Republican Campaign Plan|url=http://www.news9.com/story/39824282/rep-horn-being-targeted-in-2020-republican-campaign-plan|publisher=KWTV|date=January 21, 2019|accessdate=February 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Primary Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Janet Barresi]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Charles Tuffy Pringle\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = David Hill\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Terry Neese]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Michael Ballard\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Miles V. Rahimi\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Shelli Landon\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Stephanie Bice]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Jake A. Merrick\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n====Endorsements====\n{{endorsements box\n|title = Tom Guild (D)\n|list =\n;Organizations\n* Blue America<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blueamerica.crooksandliars.com/2020/03/07/blue-america-congressional-endorsement-in-oklahoma-tom-guild/|title=Blue America Congressional Endorsement In Oklahoma: Tom Guild|website=Blue America|first=Howie|last=Klein|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{endorsements box\n|title = Kendra Horn (D)\n|list =\n;Individuals\n*[[Alex Hirsch]], writer, artist, and animator<ref>{{cite web | url=https://docquery.fec.gov/cgi-bin/fecimg/?201910159164231093 |title =  Page by Page Report Display (Page 623 of 678)}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===General Election===\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n|[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/ratings/house-race-ratings|title=2020 House Race Ratings|website=The Cook Political Report|accessdate=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|{{sort|1|Tossup}}\n|December 20, 2019\n|-\n|[[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside Elections]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insideelections.com/ratings/house/2020-house-ratings-december-16-20191|title=House Ratings|website=insideelections.com|accessdate=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|{{sort|1|Tossup}}\n|December 19, 2019\n|-\n|[[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2020 House|url=http://crystalball.centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-house/|website=centerforpolitics.org|publisher=Larry Sabato's Crystal Ball|accessdate=December 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|{{sort|1|Tossup}}\n|December 15, 2019\n|}\n\n====Polling====\n{{collapse top|1=<span style=\"font-size:88%;\">Hypothetical polling</span>|left=yes|bg=#B0CEFF;line-height:135%;|border=none}}\n;with Generic Republican\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign= bottom\n! Poll source\n! Date(s)<br />administered\n! Sample<br />size\n! Margin of<br />error\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Kendra<br>Horn (D)\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Generic Republican\n! Undecided\n|-\n|[https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls/20200311_OK.pdf Amber Integrated]\n|Mar 5-8, 2020\n|500 (LV)\n|\u00b1 4.38%\n|40%\n|{{party shading/Republican}}|'''44%'''\n|16%\n|-\n| [https://oklahoman.com/article/5650629/poll-shows-even-split-over-horns-votes-to-impeach-trump Amber Integrated (R)]\n| align=center| December 18\u201320, 2019\n| align=center| 500 (RV)\n| align=center| \u00b1 4.4%\n| align=center| 40%\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=center| 45%\n| align=center| 15%\n|-\n|}\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Oklahoma's 5th congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = TBA\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = TBA\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes =\n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes =\n| percentage =100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n;Partisan clients\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n;Official campaign websites for 1st district candidates\n* [https://kojoforcongress.com/ Kojo Asamoa-Caesar (D) for Congress]\n* [https://www.hernforcongress.com/ Kevin Hern (R) for Congress]\n\n;Official campaign websites for 2nd district candidates\n* [https://www.silkforcongress.com/ Joseph Silk (R) for Congress]\n\n;Official campaign websites for 5th district candidates\n* [http://mikeballardforcongress.com/ Michael Ballard (R) for Congress]\n* [https://janet2020.com/ Janet Barresi (R) for Congress]\n* [https://biceforcongress.com/ Stephanie Bice (R) for Congress]\n* [https://www.davidgreene.me/ David Greene (R) for Congress]\n* [https://www.davidhillforok.com/ David Hill (R) for Congress]\n* [https://www.kendrahornforcongress.com/ Kendra Horn (D) for Congress]\n* [https://neeseforcongress.com/ Terry Neese (R) for Congress]\n* [https://www.vansantforcongress.com/ Merideth VanSant (R) for Congress]\n\n{{2020 United States elections}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States House of Representatives elections|Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma|2020]]\n[[Category:2020 Oklahoma elections|House]]\n{{Oklahoma-election-stub}}\n", "name_user": "PutItOnAMap", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_United_States_House_of_Representatives_elections_in_Oklahoma"}
{"title_page": "Shane McMahon", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman and professional wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shane McMahon\n| image              = Shane McMahon.jpg\n| caption            = McMahon in April 2018\n| birthname          = Shane Brandon McMahon\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1970|1|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]], United States<ref>{{cite book|title=WWE Unscripted|editor1-last=Leiker|editor1-first=Ken|editor2-last=Vancil|editor2-first=Mark|publisher=[[Pocket Books]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/unscriptedwwe00kenl_0/page/201 201]|year=2003|isbn=978-0-7434-7761-1|url=https://archive.org/details/unscriptedwwe00kenl_0/page/201}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Businessman, [[professional wrestler]]\n| title              = Founder and [[Chairperson|executive vice chairman]] of Ideanomics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ideanomics.gcs-web.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors|title=Ideanomics|website=ideanomics.gcs-web.com|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n| years_active       = 1990\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Marissa Mazzola|1996}}\n| children           = 3\n| parents            = [[Vince McMahon]]<br>[[Linda McMahon]]\n| family             = [[McMahon family|McMahon]]\n| module             = {{Infobox professional wrestler|child=yes\n|names = '''Shane McMahon'''<br>Shane Stevens\n|height = 6 ft 2 in<ref name=\"WWE Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/shanemcmahon|title=Shane McMahon's WWE bio|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref>\n|weight = 230 lb<ref name=\"WWE Alumni\"/>\n|billed = [[Greenwich, Connecticut]]<br>New York City<ref name=\"WWE Alumni\"/>\n|debut = 1988\n|trainer = [[Tom Prichard]]<ref name=\"WWE Podcast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2016/0523/612047/live-coverage-of-mick-foley-wwe-network-podcast-with-shane/|title=Shane McMahon Talks Vince McMahon Relationship, Growing Up In WWE, Triple H, Undertaker, More|publisher=Wrestling Inc|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref><br>[[Al Snow]]<ref name=\"WWE Podcast\"/><br>[[Phil Nurse]]<ref name=\"WWE Podcast\"/><br>[[Sgt. Slaughter]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Shane Brandon McMahon'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp|title=WWE|accessdate=June 15, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070430120945/http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = April 30, 2007}}</ref> (born January 15, 1970)<ref name=\"Shane McMahon FAQs\">{{cite web|url=http://faqs.ign.com/articles/637/637017p1.html| title= WrestleMania X8 Shane McMahon FAQ \u2013 IGN FAQs|accessdate=August 6, 2007 |website= IGN.com}}</ref> is an American businessman and [[professional wrestler]]. He is the [[Chairperson|executive vice-chairman]] of Ideanomics, formerly Seven Stars Cloud Group. He is also a minority owner and [[Road agent (professional wrestling)|producer]] in [[WWE]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nMcMahon is a fourth generation wrestling promoter as a member of the [[McMahon family]]. He began working in WWE at age 15, starting in their warehouse, where he filled merchandise orders. McMahon was also a referee, producer, announcer, and eventually a wrestler on-screen, while also becoming WWE's Executive Vice President of Global Media behind the scenes. He is the great-grandson of [[Jess McMahon]], grandson of [[Vincent J. McMahon]], son of WWE Majority Owner/Chairman/CEO [[Vince McMahon]] and former [[Administrator of the Small Business Administration]] [[Linda McMahon]], elder brother of WWE executive/personality [[Stephanie McMahon]], and brother-in-law of WWE executive/wrestler [[Triple H|Paul Levesque]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/inside/news/shanemcmahonresigns|title=Shane McMahon resigns|website=WWE}}</ref> As a wrestler, he has won the [[WWE European Championship|European Championship]] [[List of WWE European Champions|once]], the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] [[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|once]], the [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship|SmackDown Tag Team Championship]] [[List of WWE SmackDown Tag Team Champions|once]], and the [[WWE World Cup]] in 2018.\n\nIn 2009, McMahon announced his resignation from WWE. He later became CEO of entertainment service company YOU On Demand in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Middleton|first1=Marc|title=News On Shane McMahon's Employment With YOD In China, More Speculation On His WWE Future|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2016/0224/607992/news-on-shane-mcmahon-employment-with-yod-in-china/|website=Wrestling Inc.|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> On July 12, 2013, McMahon voluntarily stepped down as CEO of YOU On Demand and appointed Weicheng Liu as his successor, while remaining the company's principal executive officer and Vice Chairman of the Board. In 2016, he returned to the WWE as an on-screen character. In 2019, McMahon was \"[[kayfabe|fired]]\" from the company after losing a match to [[Kevin Owens]], as per match stipulation.\n\n== Early life ==\nShane Brandon McMahon was born on January 15, 1970, in Gaithersburg, Maryland, to [[Vince McMahon]] and [[Linda McMahon]].<ref name=\"Shane McMahon FAQs\"/> He has one sister, [[Stephanie McMahon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp|title=WWE|accessdate=June 15, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070430120945/http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = April 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment ===\n\n==== Early years (1988\u22121997) ====\nMcMahon began his on-screen career as a referee named Shane Stevens.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Amazing But True...|date=November 2007|pages=96}}</ref><ref>WWE Magazine (November 2007). \"Shane McMaho\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1n in pinstripes\". Things you never knew : 96.</ref> As Shane Stevens, McMahon refereed during the inaugural [[Royal Rumble (1988)|1988 Royal Rumble]] [[Royal Rumble#Match|match]], and in 1990 he was the first performer to walk out to greet the audience at [[WrestleMania VI]]. McMahon soon left behind his refereeing duties and took on the role of a backstage official at [[WrestleMania VIII]] in an attempt to break up a storyline brawl between [[Randy Savage]] and [[Ric Flair]]. McMahon would then mainly work behind the scenes, launching WWF.com in 1997.\n\n==== The Corporation (1998\u20132000) ====\n{{Main|The Corporation (professional wrestling)|l1=The Corporation|The Corporate Ministry}}\nShane McMahon made his first appearances as a regular on-air character in early 1998, when he was one of the main WWF executives negotiating with [[Mike Tyson]] during Tyson's heavily-hyped involvement in WrestleMania. He became a recurring part of his father's on-air [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]]. In the early days of that [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Angle|angle]], McMahon offered support for his father in cameo roles, but he did not become an [[Enforcer (professional wrestling)|enforcer]] like [[Gerald Brisco]] and [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]]. McMahon was a [[color commentator]] on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' alongside [[Jim Cornette]] and later [[Kevin Kelly (announcer)|Kevin Kelly]], and announced with [[Jerry Lawler]] on the 1999 videogame ''[[WWF Attitude]]''. Concurrently with this, Shane took on the role as a regular character, turning on his father by signing Austin to a contract after Vince demoted him to the position of referee. Yet at [[Survivor Series (1998)|Survivor Series]], Shane turned [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] by turning on Austin and became an official member of [[The Corporation (professional wrestling)|The Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/november/1998.htm|title=Survivor Series 1998 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1999, McMahon moved away from the commentary role on ''Heat'' and became a key component in the Corporation angle, winning the [[WWE European Championship|European Championship]] from [[Sean Waltman|X-Pac]].<ref name=\"European\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/euro/358602|title=Shane McMahon's European Title History|publisher=WWE.com|accessdate=July 18, 2007}}</ref> The two met in a rematch at [[WrestleMania XV]]; McMahon got help from his childhood friends the [[Mean Street Posse]] and [[Triple H]], who turned on X-Pac during the match, to retain the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/march/xv.htm|title=WrestleMania XV Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> McMahon then retired the title, wanting to retire as an \"undefeated champion\". McMahon later gave the title to [[Dennis Knight|Mideon]], who found it in McMahon's duffel bag, thus reactivating it.\n\nAfter WrestleMania, Vince briefly made his second face run and Shane took control of the Corporation. With wrestlers such as Triple H in this new faction, Shane feuded with his father and a new faction made up of former Corporation members, [[Corporate Ministry#The Union|The Union]]. On the UPN pilot for ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'', Shane joined forces with [[The Undertaker]] and the [[Ministry of Darkness]] to form the [[Corporate Ministry]]. Eventually, Vince was revealed to be the mastermind behind this faction, and his face turn was explained to be a plot to get the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWF Championship]] off Austin. Austin then met Shane and Vince in a [[ladder match]] at the [[King of the Ring#1999|King of the Ring]] for ownership of the WWF, as in the storyline, Austin had 50%, which was assigned to him by Linda and Stephanie McMahon, upset by Vince and Shane's complicity in the storyline kidnapping of Stephanie by the Corporate Ministry, while Vince and Shane each had 25%. Shane and Vince won the match when a mystery associate raised the briefcase out of Austin's reach when he climbed the ladder, allowing Vince and Shane to grab the case and regain 100% ownership of the WWF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/june/1999.htm|title=King of the Rings 1999 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> In 1999, McMahon was awarded the [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]] Rookie of the Year award but he declined to accept it stating \u201cThese are for the boys, not me\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wrestlingrumors.net/chrisbaker/here-comes-the-money-the-career-of-shane-mcmahon/|title=Here Comes the Money: The Career of Shane McMahon|date=February 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith his ownership reinstated, McMahon shifted his sights to, then [[Face (professional wrestling)|babyface]], [[Test (wrestler)|Test]], who was [[kayfabe]] dating Shane's sister, [[Stephanie McMahon|Stephanie]]. Shane disapproved of the relationship, feeling Stephanie was dating \"beneath the family's standards\", and wound up feuding with Test. With help from the Mean Street Posse, McMahon made Test's life a living hell. At [[SummerSlam (1999)|SummerSlam]], McMahon met Test in a \"Love Her or Leave Her\" match, with the stipulation being that if McMahon won the match, Test and Stephanie could no longer see each other, and if he lost, McMahon would give his blessings to the pair. Test was able to get the win, and McMahon eventually settled his differences with Test, thus making his second face run by becoming his ally.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=104}}</ref> As his father, Vince, then feuded with Triple H, Shane was attacked in early December 1999 by Triple H and [[D-Generation X]] (DX). He was thrown off the stage in a gang style attack, in which Billy Gunn and Road Dogg prevented members of the Corporation from saving Shane. Later in the year, Stephanie turned heel, siding with her new kayfabe husband then-heel, Triple H (the two began their off-screen relationship around this time, but did not marry in real life until 2003). With that, the [[McMahon-Helmsley Faction]] began, and all of the other McMahons disappeared from television.\n\nAt [[No Way Out (2000)|No Way Out]], Shane made his return as a heel again by trying to help [[Big Show]] defeat [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]]; these efforts failed as Vince returned the next Monday night on ''Raw Is War'', when the Rock got a rematch against Big Show, and helped The Rock win the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/february/2000.htm|title=No Way Out 2000 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> This started the road to [[WrestleMania 2000]], where in the four-way main event each wrestler had a McMahon in his corner. The Rock had Vince, Big Show had Shane, Triple H had Stephanie, and [[Mick Foley]] had Shane's mother, [[Linda McMahon]]. Big Show was the first man eliminated,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/march/xvi.htm|title=WrestleMania 2000 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> and soon after he and Shane went their separate ways. This led to a match between the two at [[WWE Judgment Day#2000|Judgment Day]], which McMahon won after receiving help from Test and [[Matt Bloom|Albert]], amongst others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/may/2000.htm|title=Judgment Day 2000 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> Over the course of the next several months, McMahon allied himself with other heel wrestlers, specially [[Chris Benoit]] in his feud over the WWF Championship with The Rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/tv/raw/000710.htm|title=Raw is War \u2013 July 10, 2000 Results|accessdate=March 15, 2015|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> He was also aligned with [[Edge and Christian]], who helped him win the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] from [[Steve Blackman]].<ref name=\"Hardcore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/hard/|title=Shane McMahon's Hardcore Title History|publisher=WWE.com|accessdate=July 18, 2007}}</ref> McMahon met Blackman in a rematch at [[SummerSlam (2000)|SummerSlam]], losing the title after falling {{convert|50|ft|m}} through the stage. McMahon climbed up the set and tried to run away from Blackman, who gave chase and hit Shane with a [[Shinai|Singapore cane]], knocking him off.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=106}}</ref> McMahon then disappeared from television, making occasional cameo appearances.\n\n==== The Alliance (2001\u20132002) ====\n{{Main|The Invasion (professional wrestling)|l1=The Invasion|The Alliance (professional wrestling)|l2=The Alliance}}\nIn 2001, Shane made his third face run by once again feuding with his father, Vince. The feud with Vince was due to the elder McMahon's (kayfabe) affair with [[Trish Stratus]] and Vince's spite and demand to divorce Linda McMahon. As fate would have it, rival [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) was sold to the World Wrestling Federation (WWF) one week before the Father versus Son match at WrestleMania X-Seven. In [[Kayfabe|terms of the storyline]], Vince demanded that [[Ted Turner]] sign the contract at [[WrestleMania X-Seven]]. With Vince's ego getting the best of him, Shane was able to seize the opportunity and purchase WCW himself, to the shock of Vince. McMahon defeated his father at WrestleMania X-Seven, in a [[Hardcore wrestling|Street Fight]].<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=107}}</ref> At [[Backlash (2001)|Backlash]], McMahon debuted his [[Music in professional wrestling|theme song]] \"Here Comes The Money\" and was in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Last Man Standing match|Last Man Standing match]] against Big Show. McMahon performed the ''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving elbow drop|Leap of Faith]]'' (from the top of the scaffolding), knocking himself and Show out. [[Test (wrestler)|Test]] helped McMahon to his feet, causing McMahon to get the victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/backlash.html#01|title=Backlash 2001 Results|accessdate=May 25, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon then began a feud with [[Kurt Angle]]. By the [[King of the Ring (2001)|King of the Ring]], on June 24, McMahon's feud with Angle had culminated. After already participating in two tournament matches that night, Angle wrestled McMahon in a Street Fight. After a suplex on the hard floor, Angle was thought to have cracked his [[Coccyx|tailbone]]. Angle also delivered an [[Suplex#Belly to belly suplex|overhead belly to belly suplex]] through the plated glass stage set, but McMahon did not break through on the first attempt, causing him to fall head-first onto the concrete floor. After a successful second attempt, Angle was to put him through a second plate back out to the stage and again failed two more times. The match also had Shane missing a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Shooting star press|shooting star press]] and ended with Angle performing the [[Professional wrestling throws#Olympic slam|Angle Slam]] off the top rope before scoring the victory over a bloodied McMahon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/june/2001.htm|title=King of the Ring 2001 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon then began to lead his WCW wrestlers against his father and the WWF wrestlers, eventually turning heel by joining forces with [[Paul Heyman]] and his brand of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] (ECW) wrestlers, along with their new owner, McMahon's sister Stephanie McMahon-Helmsley. Calling themselves The Alliance, they pledged to finally run the WWF (and specifically their father) out of business. Ultimately, [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|The Invasion]] came to a head at [[Survivor Series (2001)|Survivor Series]] in a match to determine [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|which power would ultimately have control]]. The team, each respectively representing The Alliance and the WWF, of McMahon, Stone Cold Steve Austin, Kurt Angle, [[Rob Van Dam]], and [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] lost to the team of The Rock, [[Chris Jericho]], The Undertaker, [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]], and Big Show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/november/2001.htm|title=Survivor Series 2001 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Vince publicly fired both Shane and Stephanie, which Shane took in stride, admitting that he lost to the better man, while Stephanie pleaded with her father before being forcefully removed from the arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/011119.html|title=RAW results \u2013 November 19, 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Aside from a brief appearance on the July 15, 2002 episode of ''Raw'', McMahon would not be seen on television for almost two years.\n\n==== Feud with Kane and hiatus (2003\u20132005) ====\nMcMahon made his first on-screen appearance in two years on an episode of ''SmackDown!'' before [[WrestleMania XIX]], watching his father's training in the gym to prepare his match against [[Hulk Hogan]]. At WrestleMania XIX, he went to check on his father's welfare following a Street Fight with Hulk Hogan, with Hogan welcoming Shane in the ring and then walking out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/march/xix.htm|title=WrestleMania XIX Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> He turned face once more in the summer of 2003 for the first time since early 2001 by getting involved in a feud with [[Eric Bischoff]], who had made improper remarks and gestures to Shane's mother Linda. He defeated Bischoff in a Street Fight at [[SummerSlam (2003)|SummerSlam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=113\u2013114}}</ref> McMahon also got involved in a bitter rivalry with Kane after Kane gave Linda a ''[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Kneeling reverse pildriver|Tombstone Piledriver]]'' because she did not name him the number one contender to the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]]. Their feud culminated in McMahon losing a [[Professional wrestling match types#Last Man Standing match|Last Man Standing match]] at [[Unforgiven (2003)|Unforgiven]] and to a first ever [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Ambulance match]] which he lost after a match at [[Survivor Series (2003)|Survivor Series]].<ref name=\"PS112\">{{cite news|author=Martin, Finn|title=Power Slam Magazine, issue 112|work=Goldberg grabs gold (Unforgiven 2003)|publisher=SW Publishing|date=October 22, 2003|pages=22\u201323}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work =Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=114}}</ref>\n\nAfter Survivor Series, McMahon left ''Raw'' to focus his attention on the executive creative staff and on his new family. At [[WrestleMania XX]], McMahon appeared briefly on camera during the opening of the event with Vince and his newborn son, Declan.<ref>{{cite video|date=2004|title=WrestleMania XX|medium=DVD|publisher=WWE Home Video}}</ref> On a special 3-hour episode of ''Raw'' in October 2005, billed as ''WWE Homecoming'', all four members of the McMahon family were given a ''[[Stunner (professional wrestling)|Stone Cold Stunner]]'' by Stone Cold Steve Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/051003.html|title=RAW results \u2013 October 3, 2005|accessdate=May 25, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> The following week, Vince demanded an apology from ringside commentators for not coming to his family's aid, which developed into a new feud. McMahon also appeared at [[Survivor Series (2005)|Survivor Series]], though he did not appear on television. He can be seen on the DVD extra backstage talking to [[Theodore Long]], when [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]] tried to scare off McMahon, who made no deal about it.<ref>{{cite video|date=2005|title=Survivor Series 2005|medium=DVD|publisher=WWE Home Video}}</ref>\n\n==== Feud with D-Generation X and Bobby Lashley (2006\u20132007) ====\nMcMahon turned heel in the process for the first time since mid-2001 by again siding with his father to help in the feud with [[Shawn Michaels]]. At the [[Royal Rumble (2006)|2006 Royal Rumble]], Shane eliminated Michaels by throwing him over the top rope.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/january/2006.htm|title=Royal Rumble 2006 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> After weeks of attacks from behind by Shane, one of which saw him force an unconscious Michaels to kiss Vince's rear end, Shane and Michaels faced each other in a Street Fight on the March 18, 2006 ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XXXII]]''. In a fashion similar to the real life [[Montreal Screwjob]], Shane put Michaels in the [[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]] as Vince called for the bell and gave Shane the victory.<ref name=\"PS142\">{{cite news|author=Power Slam Staff|title=Power Slam Magazine, issue 142|work=Looking at WWE: SNMW (March 18, 2006)|publisher=SW Publishing|date=April 20, 2006|page=25}}</ref> The McMahons' feud with Michaels took a religious turn after [[WrestleMania 22]], where Michaels defeated Vince McMahon. Vince claimed that Michaels's victory was a result of \"divine intervention\" and [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Book|booked]] himself and his son in a match at [[Backlash (2006)|Backlash]] against Michaels and his tag team partner \"[[God]]\". Around this time, Vince began to act strangely and at one point considered himself a god. Shane, who at this time was referred by Vince as \"the product of his semen\", teamed with Vince to defeat Michaels and \"God\" at Backlash, due to help from the [[Spirit Squad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/april/2006.htm|title=Backlash 2006 Results|accessdate=August 6, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shane-07.jpg|thumb|left|upright|McMahon in 2007]]\nThis feud later enveloped [[Triple H]], who the McMahons had enlisted to take out Michaels. Triple H was getting frustrated with this, as it was distracting from his quest to regain the [[WWE Championship]]. Triple H wound up bashing Shane with his signature weapon, the [[sledgehammer]], in what was considered to be an accident that put Shane out of the ring for a while. Vince (and later Shane, who had recovered) sought to humble Triple H and get some retribution. Triple H then began a feud with the McMahons shortly after, leading to his siding with Shawn Michaels and the reformation of DX. At [[SummerSlam (2006)|SummerSlam]], the McMahons were defeated by DX.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards| publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=121\u2013122}}</ref> About a month later at [[Unforgiven (2006)|Unforgiven]], The McMahons and then [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW World Champion]] Big Show faced DX in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match. Shane was injured after Michaels elbow dropped a chair which was around Shane's neck. DX emerged victorious at Unforgiven, and Shane disappeared from television.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=122}}</ref>\n[[File:Shane McMahon November 2008.jpg|thumb|right|McMahon in November 2008]]\nOn the March 5 episode of ''Raw'', McMahon came back to inform his father, Vince, about the \"guest referee\" for the \"Battle of the Billionaires\". He told him that their opponents on the Board of Directors had won the vote, 5\u20134. The McMahons had intended for Shane to be the referee. Instead, the guest referee turned out to be the McMahons' old rival, the Texas rattlesnake Stone Cold Steve Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070305.html|title=RAW results \u2013 March 5, 2007|accessdate=July 17, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> During the \"Battle of the Billionaires\" match at [[WrestleMania 23]], Shane's attempt to interfere on his father's behalf was stopped by Austin. During the match, Shane was able to hit the ''[[Dropkick#Corner-to-corner missile dropkick|Coast to Coast]]'' dive with a trash can into [[Bobby Lashley]]'s face.<ref>{{cite news|author=McElvaney, Kevin|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated, July 2007|work=WrestleMania 23|publisher=Kappa Publishing|date=June 2007|pages=74\u2013101}}</ref> On April 9, Shane officially joined the Vince/[[Umaga (wrestler)|Umaga]]/Lashley feud when he faced Lashley for the ECW World Championship in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Luchas de Apuestas|Title vs Hair match]] which ended in Shane getting disqualified on purpose by punching the referee. After the match, Umaga, Vince, and Shane all attacked Lashley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070409.html|title=RAW results \u2013 April 9, 2007|accessdate=July 17, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> At [[Backlash (2007)|Backlash]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]] for the ECW World Championship, Shane along with Vince and Umaga defeated Lashley for the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/april/2007.htm|title=Backlash 2007 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> Vince gained the [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pin]] making him the ECW World Champion. At [[Judgment Day (2007)|Judgment Day]], Lashley faced Shane, Vince, and Umaga again, in a rematch for the ECW World Championship. This time, Lashley won the match, but since he pinned Shane rather than Vince, Vince remained the champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/may/2007.htm|title=Judgment Day 2007 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> At [[One Night Stand (2007)|One Night Stand]], Shane and Umaga tried to help Vince retain the ECW World Championship against Lashley, but failed when Lashley [[Professional wrestling attacks#Spear|speared]] Vince and pinned him for the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/ecwonenightstand07.html|title=One Night Stand 2007 Results|accessdate=July 17, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nOn the taped episode of ''Raw'' that aired on September 3, Shane, along with his mother Linda and his sister Stephanie, made appearances to confront Vince about his illegitimate child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070903.html|title=RAW results \u2013 September 3, 2007|accessdate=September 8, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Shane then returned at [[Survivor Series (2007)|Survivor Series]] to accompany [[Hornswoggle]], alongside his father, in his match against [[The Great Khali]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Lennie|last=Difino|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/matches/433496412/results/|title=Friends in low places?|accessdate=December 26, 2007|date=November 18, 2007|publisher=WWE |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071225074733/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/matches/433496412/results/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=December 25, 2007}}</ref> After that, he was only seen on WWE's pay per view, [[No Way Out (2008)|No Way Out in 2008]] talking to Big Show after the latter had his nose legitimately broken going by the plan to push Mayweather's speed by [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] before again not being seen until June 2008.\n\n==== Feud with The Legacy and sabbatical (2008\u20132009) ====\nAfter the severe injury that Vince McMahon sustained on the June 23 episode of ''Raw'' when a sign fell on top of him during his hosting of the \"Million Dollar Mania\" sweepstakes, Shane requested for the ''Raw'' roster to stand together during what was a turbulent time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/06232008/|title=A Draft disaster|date=June 23, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 26, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/06302008/|title=Heavyweight Championship comes home|date=June 30, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 26, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> Shane's plea, however, was ignored and subsequently, Shane and his sister Stephanie urged the roster to show solidarity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/07072008/|title=Rough Night in the Big Easy|date=July 7, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 25, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/07142008/|title=Anarchy in the NC|date=July 14, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate= October 25, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> On the July 28 episode of ''Raw'', Shane made an appearance to announce [[Mike Adamle]] as his and Stephanie's choice to be the new [[Professional wrestling authority figures#General Managers|''Raw'' general manager]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/07282008/|title=That's \"Mr. Adamle\" to you|date=July 28, 2008| last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 26, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> After Adamle stepped down as general manager,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081103/|title=Raw results \u2013 November 3, 2008|date=November 3, 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=January 29, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717132218/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081103/|archivedate=July 17, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he and Stephanie became the interim on-screen authority figures for the ''Raw'' program. On the November 24 episode of ''Raw'', Shane and Stephanie argued over who was in charge, leading to Stephanie telling him that ''Raw'' is her show.<ref name=\"November 24\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081124/|title=Raw results \u2013 November 24, 2008|date=November 24, 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=April 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408183316/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081124/|archivedate=April 8, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After being slapped by Stephanie, Shane finished the segment by telling her that from that day onwards, he was going to watch Stephanie run ''Raw'' \"right into the ground\".<ref name=\"November 24\"/>\n\nAt the start of 2009, [[Randy Orton]] began a feud with the McMahon family. On the January 19 episode of ''Raw'', Orton [[Professional wrestling attacks#Punt|punted]] McMahon in the head, after he had tried to fire Orton from the company for previous comments made about Stephanie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090119/|title=Raw results \u2013 January 19, 2009|date=January 19, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=April 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401175744/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090119/|archivedate=April 1, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The following week, Shane returned to television and attacked Orton for his actions, turning face in the process for the first time since 2006. On the February 2 episode of ''Raw'', it was revealed that Orton challenged Shane to a No Holds Barred match at [[No Way Out (2009)|No Way Out]], to which he accepted,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/results/|title=Blistering Son|date=February 2, 2009|last=Adkins|first=Greg|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> but was defeated by Orton in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/matches/9274736/results/|title=Results: Legacy of Brutality|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=February 15, 2009}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Shane challenged Orton to an unsanctioned match for that episode's main event. The match ended with Orton punting Shane in the head, as well as performing an ''[[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]]'' on Stephanie McMahon.<ref name=\"February 16, 2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090216/|title=Raw results \u2013 February 16, 2009|date=February 16, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=April 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408212424/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090216/|archivedate=April 8, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nShane returned on the March 30 episode of ''Raw'', alongside Triple H and his father Vince McMahon, to confront and attack [[The Legacy (professional wrestling)|The Legacy]] (Randy Orton, [[Ted DiBiase Jr.|Ted DiBiase]], and [[Cody Rhodes]]). On the April 6 episode of ''Raw'', it was announced that Shane would compete in a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|six-man tag team match]] against The Legacy at [[Backlash (2009)|Backlash]] alongside Triple H and [[Dave Batista|Batista]], the latter of whom had returned from injury, where the stipulation was that if any member of Orton's team pinned any member of Triple H's team, Orton would win Triple H's WWE Championship; however, if any member of Orton's team was counted out or disqualified, Triple H would retain the title.<ref name=\"April 25, 2009\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/04062009/|title=Results:Bringing in the big guns|first=Aubrey|last=Sitterson|date=April 6, 2009 |accessdate=April 25, 2009}}</ref> On the May 4 episode of ''Raw'', Shane's character suffered a broken leg and ankle at the hands of Orton and Legacy as a way to write him out of the story. In October 2009, Shane announced his resignation from WWE which went into effect at the end of the year.\n\n=== Return to WWE ===\n\n==== Commissioner of SmackDown Live (2016\u20132017) ====\nOn the February 22, 2016 episode of ''Raw'', Shane returned to WWE as a face for the first time in nearly seven years, interrupting his sister, [[Stephanie McMahon]], receiving the \"[[Vincent J. McMahon]] Legacy of Excellence\" Award from their father, [[Vince McMahon]]. Shane announced that the reason he had returned was that he wanted control of ''Raw'', leading to Vince placing Shane in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match at [[WrestleMania 32]] against [[The Undertaker]], adding the stipulation that Shane would get control of ''Raw'' and Undertaker would no longer be a participant in Future Wrestlemania's if he wins the match.<ref name=\"Raw2222016\">{{cite web|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|title=WWE RAW Results - 2/22/16 (Live results from Detroit)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/57868-wwe-raw-results-2-22-16-live-results-from-detroit|website=wrestleview.com|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> At WrestleMania, Shane attempted a Leap of Faith off the top of the cell but Undertaker moved out of the way and Shane fell through an announce table. Shane was defeated by Undertaker soon after.\n[[File:Shane McMahon Raw 2016.jpg|thumb|upright|McMahon during a [[WWE Raw|Raw]] show in April 2016]]\nDespite losing at WrestleMania, Shane controlled ''Raw'' for a month, firstly by his father, Vince, on the ''Raw'' after WrestleMania, then for the following three weeks after \"popular demand on social media\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wortman|first1=James|title=Shane McMahon will return to run Raw for the third consecutive week|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2016-04-18/article/might-shane-mcmahon-run-his-third-consecutive-raw|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref> This led to Stephanie confronting Shane, telling him that their father will decide who will control ''Raw'' at [[Payback (2016)|Payback]], where Vince announced that both Shane and Stephanie would be Co-general managers and have joint control of WWE.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Clapp|first1=John|title=Mr. McMahon will announce who controls Raw at WWE Payback|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwepayback/2016/article/mr-mcmahon-announce-who-controls-raw|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Meltzer|first1=Dave|authorlink1=Dave Meltzer|title=WWE Payback live results: Roman Reigns vs. AJ Styles; Kevin Owens vs. Sami Zayn|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-payback-live-results-roman-reigns-vs-aj-styles-kevin-owens-vs-sami-zayn-212001|website=f4wonline.com|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pruett|first1=Will|title=Pruett's Pause: WWE Payback 2016|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2016/05/02/pruetts-pause-wwe-payback-2016-a-new-era-begins-with-the-same-tired-playbook-run-ins-galore-a-montreal-finish-and-dueling-mcmahons/|website=prowrestling.net|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July, after the announcement of the return of the [[WWE brand extension|brand extension]] with ''[[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]]'' moving to Tuesday and airing live weekly, Vince appointed Shane as the storyline commissioner of the SmackDown brand and Stephanie as the commissioner of Raw before tasking them to name a general manager for their respective shows. Shane appointed [[Daniel Bryan]] as the general manager of ''SmackDown''. At [[SummerSlam (2016)|SummerSlam]] on August 21, [[Brock Lesnar]] won his match against [[Randy Orton]] by [[technical knockout]] and continued to assault Orton as he was being tended to. Shane then confronted Lesnar, which resulted in Shane being attacked by Lesnar with a F-5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/wwe/story/brock-lesnar-bloodies-randy-orton-f5s-shane-mcmahon-at-summerslam-082116|title=Brock Lesnar F5's Shane McMahon at Summerslam|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> On the November 8 episode of ''SmackDown'', Shane agreed to replace an injured [[Baron Corbin]] in the traditional [[Survivor Series#Survivor Series matches|Survivor Series tag team elimination match]] between the two brands. At [[Survivor Series (2016)|Survivor Series]], Team SmackDown defeated Team Raw. McMahon suffered a legitimate concussion following a spear from [[Roman Reigns]], resulting in his elimination. In December, McMahon would take over host duties for ''Talking Smack'' with Daniel Bryan taking time off for family reasons.\n\nOn the February 21, 2017 episode of ''SmackDown'', after [[A.J. Styles|AJ Styles]] and [[Luke Harper]] simultaneously eliminated each other in a number one contenders battle royal as the final two entrants, McMahon made a singles match between the two for the February 28 episode of ''SmackDown'' with the winner going on to face [[Bray Wyatt]] for the WWE Championship at [[WrestleMania 33]]. Styles would originally go on to win the match before McMahon would restart the contest due to Harper having his foot on the rope during the pinfall. After McMahon accidentally distracted Harper, Styles would capitalise and pin Harper once again. That same week, after Randy Orton turned on Wyatt and cashed in his Royal Rumble winning opportunity, McMahon would go on to book a number one contender's match and the now even more infuriated Styles lost to Orton on the March 7 episode of ''SmackDown''. After losing the match, Styles would confront McMahon in the Gorilla position with things getting physical between the pair. The following week, Styles attacked McMahon inside the parking lot, which caused McMahon to be busted open and suffer a storyline concussion. Due to this, Styles was (kayfabe) \"fired\" from SmackDown. However, as McMahon was about to leave, he went back to the arena and announced that he will face Styles at WrestleMania 33. On April 2, at WrestleMania 33, McMahon lost to AJ Styles in a singles match. On April 4, the first episode of ''SmackDown'' after WrestleMania, McMahon and Styles shook hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewrestling.com/article/aj-styles-teases-babyface-turn-post-wrestlemania-33-edition-sd-live|title=AJ Styles Teases Babyface Turn At Post-WrestleMania 33 Edition Of SD! Live {{!}} EWrestling|website=ewrestling.com|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==== Feud with Kevin Owens and Sami Zayn (2017\u20132018) ====\nOn the August 1 episode of ''SmackDown'', McMahon had a serious argument with [[Kevin Owens]] due to losing to AJ Styles for the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]]. Owens demanded a competent referee, so Daniel Bryan chose McMahon to become the special guest referee. The following week on ''SmackDown'', McMahon was accidentally attacked by Styles during a brawl between Styles and Owens. Following the incident, on the August 15 episode of ''SmackDown'', McMahon warned Styles that if he puts his hands on him, he will put his hands on Styles. The warning later came to Owens after he accidentally attacked McMahon. At [[SummerSlam (2017)|SummerSlam]], McMahon was about to count the pin and declare Owens the winner, however after seeing Styles' foot on the bottom rope, McMahon continued the match. A frustrated Owens pushed McMahon, causing Shane to push him back. This caused a distraction for Styles to win back the United States Championship. On the August 22 episode of ''SmackDown'', McMahon allowed a rematch between Styles and Owens. During the match. Shane made himself referee after seeing the poor officiating from guest referee Baron Corbin, which caused a confrontation from Owens. This allowed Styles to take advantage and pin Owens to retain the championship. On the September 5 episode of ''SmackDown'', after a brief confrontation with [[Kevin Owens]], McMahon proceeded to beat down Owens after warning him not to talk about his family. Soon after, [[Daniel Bryan]] then came out to announce that Shane had been \"suspended indefinitely\" by [[Vince McMahon]], who would be returning to ''Smackdown Live'' next week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/2017-09-05/article/shane-mcmahon-suspended-as-smackdown-live-commissioner|title=Shane McMahon suspended indefinitely|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> On the September 12 episode of ''SmackDown'', CEO and Chairman of WWE, [[Vince McMahon]] announced that Shane will be facing [[Kevin Owens]] at [[Hell in a Cell (2017)|Hell in a Cell]], in a [[Hell in a Cell match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Shane McMahon vs. Kevin Owens (Hell in a Cell Match)|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/hellinacell/2017/shane-mcmahon-vs-kevin-owens-hell-in-a-cell-match|work=WWE|accessdate=September 12, 2017}}</ref> In McMahon's first pay-per-view main event since 2001, Owens won after being saved by [[Sami Zayn]] from McMahon's Leap of Faith from the top of the Cell to the announcer's table, then was dragged by Zayn to pin McMahon.\n\nOn the 23 October episode of ''Raw'', Shane McMahon fired the first shot in the build of the Smackdown vs Raw feud for [[Survivor Series (2017)|Survivor Series]] when he appeared with most of the ''SmackDown'' roster to attack the Raw roster, after initially being friendly with [[Kurt Angle]] earlier on in the same night. They proceeded to beat up wrestlers part of the ''Raw'' roster and bring Angle back to the ring. Then, Shane told Angle to bring his [[gold medal]] and the remains of the roster to Survivor Series and that at Survivor Series, they will finish what they started.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2017/1023/633372/big-spoilers-on-john-cena-wwe-survivor-series-role/|title=Big Spoilers On John Cena's WWE Survivor Series Role, RAW Vs. SmackDown Matches, Tonight's RAW, More - WrestlingInc.com|work=WrestlingInc.com|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en}}</ref> However, several weeks later, on the November 14th edition of ''SmackDown'', during the main event between The New Day vs Kevin Owens and Sami Zayn, The Shield announced their presence and came down to the ring to face The New Day in payback for The New Day's distraction on the November 6th episode of ''Raw'' costing [[Seth Rollins]] and [[Dean Ambrose]] the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]. Worse was to come, as when [[The Usos]] tried to help, they were attacked by Cesaro and Sheamus, the Raw Women locker room attacked the SmackDown Women' locker room, and when the rest of the SmackDown male roster came down with Shane to the ring to help, they were attacked in turn by the rest of the Raw male roster, including Angle and Braun Strowman. Shane was given two triple powerbombs by The Shield, and an Angle Slam by Angle, as retribution for the trouble the ''SmackDown'' roster pulled on ''Raw'' the last couple of weeks, and to prove that come the pay-per-view, Team Raw would be victorious over Team SmackDown. At Survivor Series, Shane was the last man to be eliminated by Triple H, meaning Team SmackDown lost.\n[[File:ShaneMcMahon WM34 crop.jpg|thumb|upright|McMahon at [[WrestleMania 34]]]]\nOn March 11, 2018 at [[Fastlane (2018)|Fastlane]], Shane McMahon pulled the referee out of the ring when Kevin Owens covered Dolph Ziggler and pulled Sami Zayn out of the ring when he covered Kevin Owens. On the March 13 episode of SmackDown Live, Shane McMahon announced his indefinite leave of absence as SmackDown's commissioner. Kevin Owens and Sami Zayn then proceeded to attack Shane McMahon in the ring and behind the entrance. Shane (kayfabe) suffered laryngeal contusion, trapezius and rhomboid strains. He was then taken to a local medical facility. On March 26, 2018, WWE.com reported that Shane legitimately had acute diverticulitis while resting with his family in the Caribbean on March 14, and was hospitalized in Antigua for a few days before he was moved to a hospital in New York where doctors also found that Shane has an umbilical hernia that requires surgery once the infection is eradicated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/article/shane-mcmahon-hospitalized|title=Shane McMahon hospitalized with diverticulitis|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> McMahon posted the below message to his [[Instagram]] account: \"Thank you everyone for the get well wishes. It truly helps. I'm healing up, and I have the best medicine in the world with me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/Bg1Q1swh2MG/|title= Shane McMahon (@shanemcmahonwwe)|publisher= [[Instagram]]}}</ref>\nIt was later announced that Shane would team up with [[Daniel Bryan]] against Owens and Zayn at [[WrestleMania 34]]. Shane returned on the April 3 episode of ''SmackDown Live'', to address his WrestleMania match, saying that Owens and Zayn would never be seen on a Smackdown Live arena again. At the event, Bryan and Shane defeated Zayn and Owens.\n\nHe then competed at the [[WWE Greatest Royal Rumble|Greatest Royal Rumble]], where he entered the namesake match at #47 before being eliminated after getting chokeslammed off the top rope through a table by [[Braun Strowman]]. Then, he took time off to heal from the injuries he suffered two months prior, returning on the [[SmackDown 1000|1000th edition of ''SmackDown'']] on October 16 alongside [[Stephanie McMahon]] and [[Vince McMahon]] on the ''Truth TV'' segment hosted by [[Ron Killings|R-Truth]] and [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]]. Following [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2018)|TLC: Tables, Ladders, & Chairs]] in December, The McMahon Family (Vince, Stephanie, Shane, and Triple H) appeared on ''Raw'' and announced that they would be running both Raw and SmackDown as a group with no general managers.\n\n==== Best in the World (2018\u20132019) ====\nAt the [[Crown Jewel (2018)|Crown Jewel]] event in November, he replaced [[The Miz]] after the latter suffered a (kayfabe) injury in the finals of the [[WWE World Cup]], and won by defeating [[Dolph Ziggler]] [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#Squash|in under three minutes]], winning the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-smackdown-results-recap-grades-wrestlemania-season-comes-to-an-eventful-conclusion/|title=WWE SmackDown results, recap, grades: WrestleMania season comes to an eventful conclusion|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> The Miz then began a pursuit to form a tag team with Shane, who finally agreed, and the two faced SmackDown Tag Team Champions [[Cesaro and Sheamus|The Bar]] ([[Cesaro (wrestler)|Cesaro]] and [[Sheamus]]) at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|Royal Rumble]] pay-per-view, winning the titles. At [[Elimination Chamber (2019)|Elimination Chamber]] the following month, however, they lost the titles to [[The Usos]] (Jey Uso and Jimmy Uso),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2819445-the-usos-stun-miz-shane-mcmahon-win-tag-team-title-at-wwe-elimination-chamber|title=The Usos Stun Miz, Shane McMahon, Win Tag Team Title at WWE Elimination Chamber|last=Chiari|first=Mike|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref> and failed to regain them at [[Fastlane (2019)|Fastlane]], after which, McMahon attacked The Miz and taunted Miz's father, turning [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] for the first time since 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2822637-video-shane-mcmahon-turns-on-miz-after-losing-to-the-usos-at-wwe-fastlane-2019|title=Video: Shane McMahon Attacks Miz After Losing to The Usos at WWE Fastlane 2019|last=Chiari|first=Mike|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref> McMahon then heelishly began proclaiming himself as the \"Best in the World\" and scheduled a match between himself and Miz at [[WrestleMania 35]], which Miz requested to be a Falls Count Anywhere match, and Shane agreed. At WrestleMania, McMahon narrowly defeated Miz after being [[superplex]]ed off a 15-foot platform and landing on top of Miz for the 3 count.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/04/07/wwe-wrestlemania-35-results-shane-mcmahon-defeats-the-miz-in-stunt-filled-brawl/|title=WWE WrestleMania 35 Results: Shane McMahon Defeats The Miz In Stunt-Filled Brawl|first=Alfred|last=Konuwa|website=Forbes}}</ref> On the April 29 edition of ''Raw'', McMahon helped [[Bobby Lashley]] defeat Miz, who was [[2019 WWE Superstar Shake-up|drafted to Raw]], and then McMahon attacked Miz. Later that night, Miz challenged McMahon to a Steel Cage Match at [[Money in the Bank (2019)|Money in the Bank]], which Shane accepted.\n\nWhile simultaneously feuding with Miz on Raw, over on SmackDown, [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]] and [[Roman Reigns]] were drafted to the brand. Shane's father Vince introduced Elias as SmackDown's biggest acquisition on the April 16 episode of ''SmackDown''. The two were confronted by Reigns, who attacked Elias and attacked Vince with the Superman Punch. The following week, Shane called out Reigns for a fight for attacking his father, but Reigns was attacked from behind by Elias, who was assisted by Shane, forming an alliance between Elias and Shane. Shane then forced Reigns to face The B-Team ([[Bo Dallas]] and [[Curtis Axel]]) in a handicap match with Elias as the special referee enforcer that Reigns won. The following week on ''SmackDown'', Shane teamed with Elias, Daniel Bryan, and [[Erick Rowan|Rowan]] in a seven-man handicap match and defeated the team of  Reigns and The Usos. At Money In The Bank, Shane once again defeated The Miz this time by escaping the cage ending their feud. The following night on RAW, Shane confronted Roman Reigns with Reigns challenging Shane to a match at Super ShowDown which Shane accepted. At [[Super ShowDown (2019)|Super ShowDown]], Shane defeated Roman Reigns after interference from [[Drew McIntyre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-super-showdown/2019/roman-reigns-vs-shane-mcmahon-results|title=WWE Super ShowDown Results: \"The Best in the World\" Shane McMahon def. Roman Reigns|accessdate=June 7, 2019|author=James Wortman|publisher=[[WWE]].com}}</ref> Shane and McIntyre lost to Reigns and [[The Undertaker]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types|No Holds Barred]] tag team match at [[Extreme Rules (2019)|Extreme Rules]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|title=The Undertaker & Roman Reigns def. Shane McMahon & Drew McIntyre (No Holds Barred Match)|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/extremerules/extreme-rules-2019/undertaker-roman-reigns-vs-shane-mcmahon-drew-mcintyre-results|work=WWE|accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, McMahon re-ignited his feud with [[Kevin Owens]], after Owens stated his distaste in McMahon's constant dominance on television and began to hit him with the ''Stunner'' on countless occasions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/kevin-owens-rants-against-shane-mcmahon-smackdown-live-july-9-2019|title=Kevin Owens tears into Shane McMahon in shocking rant|via=www.wwe.com}}</ref> McMahon lost to Owens at [[SummerSlam (2019)|SummerSlam]] where had Owens lost he would have quit WWE. McMahon later replaced an injured Elias in a semi-final match against [[Chad Gable]] for the [[2019 King of the Ring]] tournament, and Owens was made the referee, and despite McMahon's promise to consider dropping a fine for Owens damaging expensive equipment, Owens allowed Gable to win, and Owens was hereby fired. However, Owens continued to appear on TV to issue legal threats, until October 4's [[WWE SmackDown's 20th Anniversary]] episode, where McMahon was \"fired\" after losing a ladder match against Owens.<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/10/04/wwe-friday-night-smackdown-results-shane-mcmahon-loses-to-kevin-owens-becomes-immediate-candidate-to-join-nxt/</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\nShane McMahon began working in WWE at age 15, starting in their warehouse, where he filled merchandise orders. McMahon was also a referee, producer, announcer, and eventually a wrestler on-screen, while also becoming WWE's Executive Vice President of Global Media behind the scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/shane-mcmahon}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2006, [[Pride Fighting Championships]] held [[Pride 32]] at the [[Thomas & Mack Center]] in [[Paradise, Nevada]]. Shane was in attendance at the event,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.foxsports.com/blogs/FOXSportsMMA/2006/10/25/Showbiz_and_MMA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106095647/http://community.foxsports.com/blogs/FOXSportsMMA/2006/10/25/Showbiz_and_MMA|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 6, 2006|title=Showbiz and MMA \u2013 Dave Doyle's FOXSports.com MMA Blog \u2013 FOX Sports Blogs|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref> resulting in speculation that WWE could be considering promoting MMA events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightopinion.com/2006/10/22/is-wwe-getting-into-the-mma-business/|title=FightOpinion.com \u2013 Your Global Connection to the Fight Industry|accessdate= May 25, 2007}}</ref> On November 17, WWE and [[Dream Stage Entertainment]] officials, the parent company of Pride Fighting Championships, had a meeting at WWE global headquarters in [[Stamford, Connecticut]]. The meeting focused on the possibility of the two groups doing some form of business together in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/archive/34401241|title=Update on PRIDE \u2013 WWE meeting|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref> Yet on March 27, 2007, [[Nobuyuki Sakakibara]], president of DSE, announced that [[Station Casinos]], Inc. magnate Lorenzo Fertitta, also one of the co-owners of Zuffa, the parent company of the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], had made a deal to acquire all the assets of Pride FC from DSE after [[Pride 34]] in a deal worth about US$70 million, thereby ceasing any prospective business between Pride and WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.pridefc.com/pride2005/index.php?mainpage=news&news_id=1035|title=\"Japanese Magazine \"Kamipro\" Interview with DSE President Nobuyuki Sakakibara|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nLater in November, McMahon and WWE Canada President [[Carl De Marco]] traveled to South America to finalize a major TV deal in [[Brazil]], which allowed their television station to air ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' and ''[[WWE Friday Night SmackDown|SmackDown]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2007_/articles/1196108928.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128223206/http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2007_/articles/1196108928.php|url-status=dead|title=Sid Vicious Talking With Vince McMahon; Shane McMahon Update, House Show Draws Lackluster Crowd|archivedate=November 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, McMahon finalized another major TV deal, this time in Mexico, which allowed WWE programming to air on Mexico's two biggest television networks, ''Raw'' on [[Televisa]] and ''SmackDown'' on [[TV Azteca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/artman/publish/WWE/article1002737.shtml|title=WWE to announce another TV deal|accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2009, WWE published a statement from Shane McMahon announcing his resignation from his position as WWE's Executive Vice President of Global Media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/shanemcmahonresigns|title=Shane McMahon resigns|accessdate=October 16, 2009|publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment, Inc.}}</ref> and also issued an official press release stating that the resignation was tendered effective January 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/shanemcmahontodepartWWE|title=Shane McMahon to depart WWE|accessdate=October 16, 2009|publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment, Inc.}}</ref> No specific reason was given for the resignation. McMahon stated in the WWE press release, \"Having been associated with this organization for the majority of my life, I feel this is the opportune time in my career to pursue outside ventures.\" thus ending his 20-year stint with the company on January 1, 2010. McMahon's resignation left only two original members of the McMahon family active within the company; his father Vince, and his sister, Stephanie.\n\nOn August 3, 2010, McMahon became the CEO of China Broadband Inc., a provider of cable broadband services, as well as other digital and analog related services, in [[Shandong]] province of [[China]]. The company is based in [[Boulder County, Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1280883897|title=Shane McMahon new CEO of China Broadband Inc|publisher=Wrestle View|accessdate=August 5, 2010|date=August 3, 2010|first=Adam|last=Martin|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511065745/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1280883897|archivedate=May 11, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Also in 2010, McMahon became the CEO of You On Demand, the first [[video-on-demand]] and pay-per-view service in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/18/business/la-fi-ct-shane-mcmahon-20110618|title=Shane McMahon looking to make his mark with China venture|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2011|date=June 18, 2011|first=Joe|last=Flint}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20130217/MEDIA_ENTERTAINMENT/302179989/shane-mcmahon-goes-to-china|title=Shane McMahon goes to China|publisher=crainsnewyork.com|accessdate=February 17, 2013|date=February 17, 2013|first=Chris|last=Bragg}}</ref> In 2013, McMahon stepped down as CEO of You On Demand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/wwe/shane-mcmahon-resigns-as-ceo-of-you-on-demand/|title=Shane McMahon resigns as CEO of 'YOU on Demand'|date=2013-09-05|website=www.sportskeeda.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref> McMahon remains Executive Vice Chairman of the Board of Directors of the company, which has undergone several name changes since that time, including Wecast Holdings Inc., Seven Stars Cloud Group, Inc., and ultimately, Ideanomics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=33570440|title=Seven Stars Cloud Group, Inc.: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> The company is headquartered in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.intrinio.com/company/SSC}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2011, McMahon sits on the Board of Directors for International Sports Management representing talent such as [[Ernie Els]] and (previously<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/golf/sport/story/117175.html|title=McIlroy parts company with Chandler and ISM|accessdate=June 14, 2014|publisher=ESPN Sports Media Ltd.}}</ref>) [[Rory McIlroy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rajah.com/base/node/22531|title=Shane McMahon Update, Jericho Makes Reality Love Connection, WM28|publisher=Rajah.com|accessdate=April 12, 2011|date=April 12, 2011|first=Michael|last=Bluth}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon is also a part owner of the [[Indian Larry]] Motorcycle Shop in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|NY]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inkedmag.com/articles/question-everything|title=Question everything - Inked Magazine}}</ref>\n\nShane McMahon still remains a minority owner of WWE,<ref>{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/wwe/who-is-the-real-owner-of-wwe}}</ref> owning 2 percent of the company's shares.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/shane-mcmahon}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMcMahon is married to Marissa Mazzola.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oliver|first=Greg|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2006/07/20/1694331.html|title=Shane McMahon aiming for respect|date=|accessdate=July 7, 2018|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> They have three sons.<ref name=\"WM32 Sons\"/> His sons appeared at [[WrestleMania 32]], accompanying him to the ring in his match against [[The Undertaker]]; they have also been seen in the crowd for some of his more recent matches.<ref name=\"WM32 Sons\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/wwe/story/wwe-wrestlemania-32-shane-mcmahon-entrance-with-his-three-sons-040316|title=Shane McMahon makes WrestleMania 32 entrance with his three sons|last=Werner|first=Barry|website=[[Foxsports.com]]|date=April 3, 2016|access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon usually wears baseball jerseys for his matches, with the front saying \"Shane O Mac\" and the back reserved for \"McMahon\", the name of the pay-per-view in which he's participating, or some other phrase relating to the match and/or his opponent. When his father, [[Vince McMahon|Vince]], was interviewed in ''[[Playboy]]'', he mentioned that although Shane is [[right-handed]], he often throws left-handed punches. McMahon's football jersey number was 61,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/pictures/s/shanemcmahon/01.jpg|title=Shane McMahon's football jersey number|accessdate= August 6, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> the same as his father.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/pictures/f/football/vince.jpg|title=Shane and Vince's football jersey number|accessdate= August 6, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> On July 19, 2017, McMahon was involved in a helicopter crash, but was relatively unharmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tmz.com/2017/07/19/wwe-shane-mcmahon-helicopter-crash-atlantic-ocean/|title=WWE'S SHANE MCMAHONHELICOPTER CRASHES... Escapes Uninjured|author=TMZ staff|work=[[TMZ]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Other media ==\nIn September 2006, he was named one of ''[[Details (magazine)|Detail]]'' magazine's \"50 Most Powerful Men Under 42\" in the annual \"power issue\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://men.style.com/details/features/full?id=content_4990&pageNum=17|title=The Power 50: Details Article on men.style.com|accessdate=July 17, 2007|work=[[Details (magazine)|Detail Magazine]]|date=October 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927224324/http://men.style.com/details/features/full?id=content_4990&pageNum=17|archivedate=September 27, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Filmography ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Feature films\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Note\n|-\n|1999 || ''[[Beyond the Mat|Beyond The Mat]]'' || Himself || [[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n|-\n|2002 || ''[[Rollerball (2002 film)|Rollerball]]'' || American Media Mogul ||Cameo appearance\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Note\n|-\n|2019 || ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]'' || [[United States Army Criminal Investigation Command|US Army CID]] Special Agent Steve Evans || 2 episodes\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year !! Title\n! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1999 || ''[[WWF Attitude]]''\n|Voice Only\n|-\n| ''[[WWF WrestleMania 2000]]''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2000 || ''[[WWF No Mercy]]''\n|\n|-\n|'' [[WWF SmackDown! (video game)|WWF SmackDown!]]''\n|\n|-\n|''[[WWF SmackDown! 2: Know Your Role]]''\n|\n|-\n|2001 || ''[[WWF SmackDown! Just Bring It]]''\n|\n|-\n|2002 || ''[[WWE WrestleMania X8]]''\n|\n|-\n|2006 || ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2007]]''\n|\n|-\n|2007 || ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2008]]''\n|\n|-\n|2008 || ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2009]]''\n|NPC\n|-\n|2009 || ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2010]]''\n|NPC\n|-\n|2012 || ''[[WWE '13]]''\n|\n|-\n|2014 || ''[[WWE SuperCard]]''\n|Latest card:<br/>WM 34\n|-\n|2015 || ''[[WWE 2K16]]''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2016 || ''[[WWE 2K17]]''\n|\n|-\n|WWE Champions\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=2|2017 || ''[[WWE 2K18]]''\n|\n|-\n|WWE Mayhem\n|\n|-\n|2018 || ''[[WWE 2K19]]''\n|\n|-\n|2019 || ''[[WWE 2K20]]''\n|\n|}\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Active awards#Feud of the Year|Feud of the Year]] (2001) {{small|vs. [[Vince McMahon]]}}<ref name=\"PWI Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pwi-online.com/pages/PWIawards.html|title=PWI Awards|work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=[[Kappa Publishing Group]]|accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref>\n** [[List of Pro Wrestling Illustrated awards#Rookie of the Year|Rookie of the Year]] (1999)<ref name=\"PWI Awards\"/>\n** Ranked No. 245 of the 500 top singles wrestlers in the [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]] in 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profightdb.com/pwi-500/1999.html|accessdate=April 3, 2015|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 1999|work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation / WWE]]'''\n**[[WWE European Championship|WWF European Championship]] ([[List of WWE European Champions|1 time]])<ref name=\"European\"/>\n** [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|1 time]])<ref name=\"Hardcore\"/>\n** [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of WWE SmackDown Tag Team Champions|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[The Miz]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sescoops.com/miz-shane-mcmahon-win-smackdown-tag-team-titles-at-wwe-royal-rumble/|title=Miz & Shane McMahon Win SmackDown Tag Team Titles At WWE Royal Rumble|last=Andrew Ravens|date=2019-01-28|website=SEScoops|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n**[[WWE World Cup]] ([[Crown Jewel (2018)#WWE World Cup|2018]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2018/11/02/wwe-crown-jewel-2018-results-shane-mcmahon-world-cup-winner-will-make-a-tremendous-heel/|title=WWE Crown Jewel 2018 Results: Shane McMahon, World Cup Winner, Will Make A Tremendous Heel|last=Konuwa|first=Alfred|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n* '''''[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n**[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Most Disgusting Promotional Tactic|Most Disgusting Promotional Tactic]] (2003) <small>McMahon family all over WWE products</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.vice.com/en_uk/article/qky387/breaking-kayfabe-an-inside-look-at-wwes-unlikely-business-empire|title=Breaking Kayfabe: An Inside Look at WWE's Unlikely Business Empire|last=Frisch|first=Ian|date=2016-12-12|website=Sports|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Feud of the Year|Worst Feud of the Year]] (2006) {{small|with Vince McMahon vs. [[D-Generation X]] ([[Shawn Michaels]] and [[Triple H]])}}{{Citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite book|author=Shawn Michaels and Aaron Feigenbaum|title=Heartbreak And Triumph: The Shawn Michaels Story|publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment|date=November 22, 2005|pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780743493802/page/352 352 pages]|isbn=978-0-7434-9380-2|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780743493802/page/352}}\n* {{cite book|author=Shaun Assael and Mike Mooneyham|title=Sex, Lies, and Headlocks: The Real Story of Vince McMahon and World Wrestling Entertainment|publisher=Crown|year=2002|pages=258 pages|isbn=1-4000-5143-6}}\n* {{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year= 2007}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Shane McMahon}}\n* {{WWE superstar}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{McMahonFamily}}\n{{WWE European Championship}}\n{{WWE Hardcore Championship}}\n{{WWE personnel}}\n{{WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship}}\n}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMahon, Shane}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Greenwich, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:People from Fire Island, New York]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York City]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers billed from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling announcers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling referees]]\n[[Category:WWF European Champions]]\n[[Category:WWE]]\n[[Category:WWE executives]]\n[[Category:McMahon family]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman and professional wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shane McMahon\n| image              = Shane McMahon.jpg\n| caption            = McMahon in April 2018\n| birthname          = Shane Brandon McMahon\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1970|1|15}}\n| birth_place        = [[Gaithersburg, Maryland]], United States<ref>{{cite book|title=WWE Unscripted|editor1-last=Leiker|editor1-first=Ken|editor2-last=Vancil|editor2-first=Mark|publisher=[[Pocket Books]]|page=[https://archive.org/details/unscriptedwwe00kenl_0/page/201 201]|year=2003|isbn=978-0-7434-7761-1|url=https://archive.org/details/unscriptedwwe00kenl_0/page/201}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Businessman, [[professional wrestler]]\n| title              = Founder and [[Chairperson|executive vice chairman]] of Ideanomics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ideanomics.gcs-web.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors|title=Ideanomics|website=ideanomics.gcs-web.com|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref>\n| years_active       = 1990\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Marissa Mazzola|1996}}\n| children           = 3\n| parents            = [[Vince McMahon]]<br>[[Linda McMahon]]\n| family             = [[McMahon family|McMahon]]\n| module             = {{Infobox professional wrestler|child=yes\n|names = '''Shane McMahon'''<br>Shane Stevens\n|height = 6 ft 2 in<ref name=\"WWE Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/shanemcmahon|title=Shane McMahon's WWE bio|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref>\n|weight = 230 lb<ref name=\"WWE Alumni\"/>\n|billed = [[Greenwich, Connecticut]]<br>New York City<ref name=\"WWE Alumni\"/>\n|debut = 1988\n|trainer = [[Tom Prichard]]<ref name=\"WWE Podcast\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2016/0523/612047/live-coverage-of-mick-foley-wwe-network-podcast-with-shane/|title=Shane McMahon Talks Vince McMahon Relationship, Growing Up In WWE, Triple H, Undertaker, More|publisher=Wrestling Inc|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref><br>[[Al Snow]]<ref name=\"WWE Podcast\"/><br>[[Phil Nurse]]<ref name=\"WWE Podcast\"/><br>[[Sgt. Slaughter]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Shane Brandon McMahon'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp|title=WWE|accessdate=June 15, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070430120945/http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = April 30, 2007}}</ref> (born January 15, 1970)<ref name=\"Shane McMahon FAQs\">{{cite web|url=http://faqs.ign.com/articles/637/637017p1.html| title= WrestleMania X8 Shane McMahon FAQ \u2013 IGN FAQs|accessdate=August 6, 2007 |website= IGN.com}}</ref> is an American businessman and [[professional wrestler]]. He is the [[Chairperson|executive vice-chairman]] of Ideanomics, formerly Seven Stars Cloud Group. He is also a minority owner and [[Road agent (professional wrestling)|producer]] in [[WWE]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nMcMahon is a fourth generation wrestling promoter as a member of the [[McMahon family]]. He began working in WWE at age 15, starting in their warehouse, where he filled merchandise orders. McMahon was also a referee, producer, announcer, and eventually a wrestler on-screen, while also becoming WWE's Executive Vice President of Global Media behind the scenes. He is the great-grandson of [[Jess McMahon]], grandson of [[Vincent J. McMahon]], son of WWE Majority Owner/Chairman/CEO [[Vince McMahon]] and former [[Administrator of the Small Business Administration]] [[Linda McMahon]], elder brother of WWE executive/personality [[Stephanie McMahon]], and brother-in-law of WWE executive/wrestler [[Triple H|Paul Levesque]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/inside/news/shanemcmahonresigns|title=Shane McMahon resigns|website=WWE}}</ref> As a wrestler, he has won the [[WWE European Championship|European Championship]] [[List of WWE European Champions|once]], the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] [[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|once]], the [[WWE SmackDown Tag Team Championship|SmackDown Tag Team Championship]] [[List of WWE SmackDown Tag Team Champions|once]], and the [[WWE World Cup]] in 2018.\n\nIn 2009, McMahon announced his resignation from WWE. He later became CEO of entertainment service company YOU On Demand in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Middleton|first1=Marc|title=News On Shane McMahon's Employment With YOD In China, More Speculation On His WWE Future|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2016/0224/607992/news-on-shane-mcmahon-employment-with-yod-in-china/|website=Wrestling Inc.|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref> On July 12, 2013, McMahon voluntarily stepped down as CEO of YOU On Demand and appointed Weicheng Liu as his successor, while remaining the company's principal executive officer and Vice Chairman of the Board. In 2016, he returned to the WWE as an on-screen character. In 2019, McMahon was \"[[kayfabe|fired]]\" from the company after losing a match to [[Kevin Owens]], as per match stipulation.\n\n== Early life ==\nShane Brandon McMahon was born on January 15, 1970, in Gaithersburg, Maryland, to [[Vince McMahon]] and [[Linda McMahon]].<ref name=\"Shane McMahon FAQs\"/> He has one sister, [[Stephanie McMahon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp|title=WWE|accessdate=June 15, 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070430120945/http://corporate.wwe.com/governance/bios/sb_mcmahon.jsp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = April 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment ===\n\n==== Early years (1988\u22121997) ====\nMcMahon began his on-screen career as a referee named Shane Stevens.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Amazing But True...|date=November 2007|pages=96}}</ref><ref>WWE Magazine (November 2007). \"Shane McMaho\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1\u00b1n in pinstripes\". Things you never knew : 96.</ref> As Shane Stevens, McMahon refereed during the inaugural [[Royal Rumble (1988)|1988 Royal Rumble]] [[Royal Rumble#Match|match]], and in 1990 he was the first performer to walk out to greet the audience at [[WrestleMania VI]]. McMahon soon left behind his refereeing duties and took on the role of a backstage official at [[WrestleMania VIII]] in an attempt to break up a storyline brawl between [[Randy Savage]] and [[Ric Flair]]. McMahon would then mainly work behind the scenes, launching WWF.com in 1997.\n\n==== The Corporation (1998\u20132000) ====\n{{Main|The Corporation (professional wrestling)|l1=The Corporation|The Corporate Ministry}}\nShane McMahon made his first appearances as a regular on-air character in early 1998, when he was one of the main WWF executives negotiating with [[Mike Tyson]] during Tyson's heavily-hyped involvement in WrestleMania. He became a recurring part of his father's on-air [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feud]] with [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]]. In the early days of that [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Angle|angle]], McMahon offered support for his father in cameo roles, but he did not become an [[Enforcer (professional wrestling)|enforcer]] like [[Gerald Brisco]] and [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]]. McMahon was a [[color commentator]] on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' alongside [[Jim Cornette]] and later [[Kevin Kelly (announcer)|Kevin Kelly]], and announced with [[Jerry Lawler]] on the 1999 videogame ''[[WWF Attitude]]''. Concurrently with this, Shane took on the role as a regular character, turning on his father by signing Austin to a contract after Vince demoted him to the position of referee. Yet at [[Survivor Series (1998)|Survivor Series]], Shane turned [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] by turning on Austin and became an official member of [[The Corporation (professional wrestling)|The Corporation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/november/1998.htm|title=Survivor Series 1998 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1999, McMahon moved away from the commentary role on ''Heat'' and became a key component in the Corporation angle, winning the [[WWE European Championship|European Championship]] from [[Sean Waltman|X-Pac]].<ref name=\"European\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/euro/358602|title=Shane McMahon's European Title History|publisher=WWE.com|accessdate=July 18, 2007}}</ref> The two met in a rematch at [[WrestleMania XV]]; McMahon got help from his childhood friends the [[Mean Street Posse]] and [[Triple H]], who turned on X-Pac during the match, to retain the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/march/xv.htm|title=WrestleMania XV Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> McMahon then retired the title, wanting to retire as an \"undefeated champion\". McMahon later gave the title to [[Dennis Knight|Mideon]], who found it in McMahon's duffel bag, thus reactivating it.\n\nAfter WrestleMania, Vince briefly made his second face run and Shane took control of the Corporation. With wrestlers such as Triple H in this new faction, Shane feuded with his father and a new faction made up of former Corporation members, [[Corporate Ministry#The Union|The Union]]. On the UPN pilot for ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'', Shane joined forces with [[The Undertaker]] and the [[Ministry of Darkness]] to form the [[Corporate Ministry]]. Eventually, Vince was revealed to be the mastermind behind this faction, and his face turn was explained to be a plot to get the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWF Championship]] off Austin. Austin then met Shane and Vince in a [[ladder match]] at the [[King of the Ring#1999|King of the Ring]] for ownership of the WWF, as in the storyline, Austin had 50%, which was assigned to him by Linda and Stephanie McMahon, upset by Vince and Shane's complicity in the storyline kidnapping of Stephanie by the Corporate Ministry, while Vince and Shane each had 25%. Shane and Vince won the match when a mystery associate raised the briefcase out of Austin's reach when he climbed the ladder, allowing Vince and Shane to grab the case and regain 100% ownership of the WWF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/june/1999.htm|title=King of the Rings 1999 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> In 1999, McMahon was awarded the [[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]] Rookie of the Year award but he declined to accept it stating \u201cThese are for the boys, not me\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wrestlingrumors.net/chrisbaker/here-comes-the-money-the-career-of-shane-mcmahon/|title=Here Comes the Money: The Career of Shane McMahon|date=February 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWith his ownership reinstated, McMahon shifted his sights to, then [[Face (professional wrestling)|babyface]], [[Test (wrestler)|Test]], who was [[kayfabe]] dating Shane's sister, [[Stephanie McMahon|Stephanie]]. Shane disapproved of the relationship, feeling Stephanie was dating \"beneath the family's standards\", and wound up feuding with Test. With help from the Mean Street Posse, McMahon made Test's life a living hell. At [[SummerSlam (1999)|SummerSlam]], McMahon met Test in a \"Love Her or Leave Her\" match, with the stipulation being that if McMahon won the match, Test and Stephanie could no longer see each other, and if he lost, McMahon would give his blessings to the pair. Test was able to get the win, and McMahon eventually settled his differences with Test, thus making his second face run by becoming his ally.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=104}}</ref> As his father, Vince, then feuded with Triple H, Shane was attacked in early December 1999 by Triple H and [[D-Generation X]] (DX). He was thrown off the stage in a gang style attack, in which Billy Gunn and Road Dogg prevented members of the Corporation from saving Shane. Later in the year, Stephanie turned heel, siding with her new kayfabe husband then-heel, Triple H (the two began their off-screen relationship around this time, but did not marry in real life until 2003). With that, the [[McMahon-Helmsley Faction]] began, and all of the other McMahons disappeared from television.\n\nAt [[No Way Out (2000)|No Way Out]], Shane made his return as a heel again by trying to help [[Big Show]] defeat [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]]; these efforts failed as Vince returned the next Monday night on ''Raw Is War'', when the Rock got a rematch against Big Show, and helped The Rock win the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/february/2000.htm|title=No Way Out 2000 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> This started the road to [[WrestleMania 2000]], where in the four-way main event each wrestler had a McMahon in his corner. The Rock had Vince, Big Show had Shane, Triple H had Stephanie, and [[Mick Foley]] had Shane's mother, [[Linda McMahon]]. Big Show was the first man eliminated,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/march/xvi.htm|title=WrestleMania 2000 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> and soon after he and Shane went their separate ways. This led to a match between the two at [[WWE Judgment Day#2000|Judgment Day]], which McMahon won after receiving help from Test and [[Matt Bloom|Albert]], amongst others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/may/2000.htm|title=Judgment Day 2000 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> Over the course of the next several months, McMahon allied himself with other heel wrestlers, specially [[Chris Benoit]] in his feud over the WWF Championship with The Rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/tv/raw/000710.htm|title=Raw is War \u2013 July 10, 2000 Results|accessdate=March 15, 2015|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> He was also aligned with [[Edge and Christian]], who helped him win the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] from [[Steve Blackman]].<ref name=\"Hardcore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/hard/|title=Shane McMahon's Hardcore Title History|publisher=WWE.com|accessdate=July 18, 2007}}</ref> McMahon met Blackman in a rematch at [[SummerSlam (2000)|SummerSlam]], losing the title after falling {{convert|50|ft|m}} through the stage. McMahon climbed up the set and tried to run away from Blackman, who gave chase and hit Shane with a [[Shinai|Singapore cane]], knocking him off.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=106}}</ref> McMahon then disappeared from television, making occasional cameo appearances.\n\n==== The Alliance (2001\u20132002) ====\n{{Main|The Invasion (professional wrestling)|l1=The Invasion|The Alliance (professional wrestling)|l2=The Alliance}}\nIn 2001, Shane made his third face run by once again feuding with his father, Vince. The feud with Vince was due to the elder McMahon's (kayfabe) affair with [[Trish Stratus]] and Vince's spite and demand to divorce Linda McMahon. As fate would have it, rival [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) was sold to the World Wrestling Federation (WWF) one week before the Father versus Son match at WrestleMania X-Seven. In [[Kayfabe|terms of the storyline]], Vince demanded that [[Ted Turner]] sign the contract at [[WrestleMania X-Seven]]. With Vince's ego getting the best of him, Shane was able to seize the opportunity and purchase WCW himself, to the shock of Vince. McMahon defeated his father at WrestleMania X-Seven, in a [[Hardcore wrestling|Street Fight]].<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=107}}</ref> At [[Backlash (2001)|Backlash]], McMahon debuted his [[Music in professional wrestling|theme song]] \"Here Comes The Money\" and was in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Last Man Standing match|Last Man Standing match]] against Big Show. McMahon performed the ''[[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Diving elbow drop|Leap of Faith]]'' (from the top of the scaffolding), knocking himself and Show out. [[Test (wrestler)|Test]] helped McMahon to his feet, causing McMahon to get the victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/backlash.html#01|title=Backlash 2001 Results|accessdate=May 25, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon then began a feud with [[Kurt Angle]]. By the [[King of the Ring (2001)|King of the Ring]], on June 24, McMahon's feud with Angle had culminated. After already participating in two tournament matches that night, Angle wrestled McMahon in a Street Fight. After a suplex on the hard floor, Angle was thought to have cracked his [[Coccyx|tailbone]]. Angle also delivered an [[Suplex#Belly to belly suplex|overhead belly to belly suplex]] through the plated glass stage set, but McMahon did not break through on the first attempt, causing him to fall head-first onto the concrete floor. After a successful second attempt, Angle was to put him through a second plate back out to the stage and again failed two more times. The match also had Shane missing a [[Professional wrestling aerial techniques#Shooting star press|shooting star press]] and ended with Angle performing the [[Professional wrestling throws#Olympic slam|Angle Slam]] off the top rope before scoring the victory over a bloodied McMahon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/june/2001.htm|title=King of the Ring 2001 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon then began to lead his WCW wrestlers against his father and the WWF wrestlers, eventually turning heel by joining forces with [[Paul Heyman]] and his brand of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] (ECW) wrestlers, along with their new owner, McMahon's sister Stephanie McMahon-Helmsley. Calling themselves The Alliance, they pledged to finally run the WWF (and specifically their father) out of business. Ultimately, [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|The Invasion]] came to a head at [[Survivor Series (2001)|Survivor Series]] in a match to determine [[Professional wrestling match types#Loser Leaves Town match|which power would ultimately have control]]. The team, each respectively representing The Alliance and the WWF, of McMahon, Stone Cold Steve Austin, Kurt Angle, [[Rob Van Dam]], and [[Booker T (wrestler)|Booker T]] lost to the team of The Rock, [[Chris Jericho]], The Undertaker, [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]], and Big Show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/november/2001.htm|title=Survivor Series 2001 Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Vince publicly fired both Shane and Stephanie, which Shane took in stride, admitting that he lost to the better man, while Stephanie pleaded with her father before being forcefully removed from the arena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/011119.html|title=RAW results \u2013 November 19, 2001|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Aside from a brief appearance on the July 15, 2002 episode of ''Raw'', McMahon would not be seen on television for almost two years.\n\n==== Feud with Kane and hiatus (2003\u20132005) ====\nMcMahon made his first on-screen appearance in two years on an episode of ''SmackDown!'' before [[WrestleMania XIX]], watching his father's training in the gym to prepare his match against [[Hulk Hogan]]. At WrestleMania XIX, he went to check on his father's welfare following a Street Fight with Hulk Hogan, with Hogan welcoming Shane in the ring and then walking out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/march/xix.htm|title=WrestleMania XIX Results|accessdate=August 22, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> He turned face once more in the summer of 2003 for the first time since early 2001 by getting involved in a feud with [[Eric Bischoff]], who had made improper remarks and gestures to Shane's mother Linda. He defeated Bischoff in a Street Fight at [[SummerSlam (2003)|SummerSlam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=113\u2013114}}</ref> McMahon also got involved in a bitter rivalry with Kane after Kane gave Linda a ''[[Piledriver (professional wrestling)#Kneeling reverse pildriver|Tombstone Piledriver]]'' because she did not name him the number one contender to the [[World Heavyweight Championship (WWE)|World Heavyweight Championship]]. Their feud culminated in McMahon losing a [[Professional wrestling match types#Last Man Standing match|Last Man Standing match]] at [[Unforgiven (2003)|Unforgiven]] and to a first ever [[Professional wrestling match types#Container-based variations|Ambulance match]] which he lost after a match at [[Survivor Series (2003)|Survivor Series]].<ref name=\"PS112\">{{cite news|author=Martin, Finn|title=Power Slam Magazine, issue 112|work=Goldberg grabs gold (Unforgiven 2003)|publisher=SW Publishing|date=October 22, 2003|pages=22\u201323}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work =Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=114}}</ref>\n\nAfter Survivor Series, McMahon left ''Raw'' to focus his attention on the executive creative staff and on his new family. At [[WrestleMania XX]], McMahon appeared briefly on camera during the opening of the event with Vince and his newborn son, Declan.<ref>{{cite video|date=2004|title=WrestleMania XX|medium=DVD|publisher=WWE Home Video}}</ref> On a special 3-hour episode of ''Raw'' in October 2005, billed as ''WWE Homecoming'', all four members of the McMahon family were given a ''[[Stunner (professional wrestling)|Stone Cold Stunner]]'' by Stone Cold Steve Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/051003.html|title=RAW results \u2013 October 3, 2005|accessdate=May 25, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> The following week, Vince demanded an apology from ringside commentators for not coming to his family's aid, which developed into a new feud. McMahon also appeared at [[Survivor Series (2005)|Survivor Series]], though he did not appear on television. He can be seen on the DVD extra backstage talking to [[Theodore Long]], when [[The Boogeyman (wrestler)|The Boogeyman]] tried to scare off McMahon, who made no deal about it.<ref>{{cite video|date=2005|title=Survivor Series 2005|medium=DVD|publisher=WWE Home Video}}</ref>\n\n==== Feud with D-Generation X and Bobby Lashley (2006\u20132007) ====\nMcMahon turned heel in the process for the first time since mid-2001 by again siding with his father to help in the feud with [[Shawn Michaels]]. At the [[Royal Rumble (2006)|2006 Royal Rumble]], Shane eliminated Michaels by throwing him over the top rope.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/january/2006.htm|title=Royal Rumble 2006 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> After weeks of attacks from behind by Shane, one of which saw him force an unconscious Michaels to kiss Vince's rear end, Shane and Michaels faced each other in a Street Fight on the March 18, 2006 ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XXXII]]''. In a fashion similar to the real life [[Montreal Screwjob]], Shane put Michaels in the [[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Sharpshooter]] as Vince called for the bell and gave Shane the victory.<ref name=\"PS142\">{{cite news|author=Power Slam Staff|title=Power Slam Magazine, issue 142|work=Looking at WWE: SNMW (March 18, 2006)|publisher=SW Publishing|date=April 20, 2006|page=25}}</ref> The McMahons' feud with Michaels took a religious turn after [[WrestleMania 22]], where Michaels defeated Vince McMahon. Vince claimed that Michaels's victory was a result of \"divine intervention\" and [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Book|booked]] himself and his son in a match at [[Backlash (2006)|Backlash]] against Michaels and his tag team partner \"[[God]]\". Around this time, Vince began to act strangely and at one point considered himself a god. Shane, who at this time was referred by Vince as \"the product of his semen\", teamed with Vince to defeat Michaels and \"God\" at Backlash, due to help from the [[Spirit Squad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/april/2006.htm|title=Backlash 2006 Results|accessdate=August 6, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shane-07.jpg|thumb|left|upright|McMahon in 2007]]\nThis feud later enveloped [[Triple H]], who the McMahons had enlisted to take out Michaels. Triple H was getting frustrated with this, as it was distracting from his quest to regain the [[WWE Championship]]. Triple H wound up bashing Shane with his signature weapon, the [[sledgehammer]], in what was considered to be an accident that put Shane out of the ring for a while. Vince (and later Shane, who had recovered) sought to humble Triple H and get some retribution. Triple H then began a feud with the McMahons shortly after, leading to his siding with Shawn Michaels and the reformation of DX. At [[SummerSlam (2006)|SummerSlam]], the McMahons were defeated by DX.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards| publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|pages=121\u2013122}}</ref> About a month later at [[Unforgiven (2006)|Unforgiven]], The McMahons and then [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|ECW World Champion]] Big Show faced DX in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match. Shane was injured after Michaels elbow dropped a chair which was around Shane's neck. DX emerged victorious at Unforgiven, and Shane disappeared from television.<ref>{{cite news|title=2007 Wrestling Almanac & Book of Facts|work=Wrestling's Historical Cards|publisher=Kappa Publishing|year=2007|page=122}}</ref>\n[[File:Shane McMahon November 2008.jpg|thumb|right|McMahon in November 2008]]\nOn the March 5 episode of ''Raw'', McMahon came back to inform his father, Vince, about the \"guest referee\" for the \"Battle of the Billionaires\". He told him that their opponents on the Board of Directors had won the vote, 5\u20134. The McMahons had intended for Shane to be the referee. Instead, the guest referee turned out to be the McMahons' old rival, the Texas rattlesnake Stone Cold Steve Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070305.html|title=RAW results \u2013 March 5, 2007|accessdate=July 17, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> During the \"Battle of the Billionaires\" match at [[WrestleMania 23]], Shane's attempt to interfere on his father's behalf was stopped by Austin. During the match, Shane was able to hit the ''[[Dropkick#Corner-to-corner missile dropkick|Coast to Coast]]'' dive with a trash can into [[Bobby Lashley]]'s face.<ref>{{cite news|author=McElvaney, Kevin|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated, July 2007|work=WrestleMania 23|publisher=Kappa Publishing|date=June 2007|pages=74\u2013101}}</ref> On April 9, Shane officially joined the Vince/[[Umaga (wrestler)|Umaga]]/Lashley feud when he faced Lashley for the ECW World Championship in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Luchas de Apuestas|Title vs Hair match]] which ended in Shane getting disqualified on purpose by punching the referee. After the match, Umaga, Vince, and Shane all attacked Lashley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070409.html|title=RAW results \u2013 April 9, 2007|accessdate=July 17, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> At [[Backlash (2007)|Backlash]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Handicap match|handicap match]] for the ECW World Championship, Shane along with Vince and Umaga defeated Lashley for the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/april/2007.htm|title=Backlash 2007 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> Vince gained the [[Pin (professional wrestling)|pin]] making him the ECW World Champion. At [[Judgment Day (2007)|Judgment Day]], Lashley faced Shane, Vince, and Umaga again, in a rematch for the ECW World Championship. This time, Lashley won the match, but since he pinned Shane rather than Vince, Vince remained the champion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwwew.net/ppv/wwf/may/2007.htm|title=Judgment Day 2007 Results|accessdate=August 14, 2007|publisher=PWWEW.net}}</ref> At [[One Night Stand (2007)|One Night Stand]], Shane and Umaga tried to help Vince retain the ECW World Championship against Lashley, but failed when Lashley [[Professional wrestling attacks#Spear|speared]] Vince and pinned him for the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/wweppv/ecwonenightstand07.html|title=One Night Stand 2007 Results|accessdate=July 17, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\nOn the taped episode of ''Raw'' that aired on September 3, Shane, along with his mother Linda and his sister Stephanie, made appearances to confront Vince about his illegitimate child.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/070903.html|title=RAW results \u2013 September 3, 2007|accessdate=September 8, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> Shane then returned at [[Survivor Series (2007)|Survivor Series]] to accompany [[Hornswoggle]], alongside his father, in his match against [[The Great Khali]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Lennie|last=Difino|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/matches/433496412/results/|title=Friends in low places?|accessdate=December 26, 2007|date=November 18, 2007|publisher=WWE |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071225074733/http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/matches/433496412/results/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=December 25, 2007}}</ref> After that, he was only seen on WWE's pay per view, [[No Way Out (2008)|No Way Out in 2008]] talking to Big Show after the latter had his nose legitimately broken going by the plan to push Mayweather's speed by [[Floyd Mayweather Jr.]] before again not being seen until June 2008.\n\n==== Feud with The Legacy and sabbatical (2008\u20132009) ====\nAfter the severe injury that Vince McMahon sustained on the June 23 episode of ''Raw'' when a sign fell on top of him during his hosting of the \"Million Dollar Mania\" sweepstakes, Shane requested for the ''Raw'' roster to stand together during what was a turbulent time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/06232008/|title=A Draft disaster|date=June 23, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 26, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/06302008/|title=Heavyweight Championship comes home|date=June 30, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 26, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> Shane's plea, however, was ignored and subsequently, Shane and his sister Stephanie urged the roster to show solidarity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/07072008/|title=Rough Night in the Big Easy|date=July 7, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 25, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/07142008/|title=Anarchy in the NC|date=July 14, 2008|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate= October 25, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> On the July 28 episode of ''Raw'', Shane made an appearance to announce [[Mike Adamle]] as his and Stephanie's choice to be the new [[Professional wrestling authority figures#General Managers|''Raw'' general manager]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/07282008/|title=That's \"Mr. Adamle\" to you|date=July 28, 2008| last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|accessdate=October 26, 2008|publisher=WWE}}</ref> After Adamle stepped down as general manager,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081103/|title=Raw results \u2013 November 3, 2008|date=November 3, 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=January 29, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717132218/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081103/|archivedate=July 17, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> he and Stephanie became the interim on-screen authority figures for the ''Raw'' program. On the November 24 episode of ''Raw'', Shane and Stephanie argued over who was in charge, leading to Stephanie telling him that ''Raw'' is her show.<ref name=\"November 24\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081124/|title=Raw results \u2013 November 24, 2008|date=November 24, 2008|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=April 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408183316/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_081124/|archivedate=April 8, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After being slapped by Stephanie, Shane finished the segment by telling her that from that day onwards, he was going to watch Stephanie run ''Raw'' \"right into the ground\".<ref name=\"November 24\"/>\n\nAt the start of 2009, [[Randy Orton]] began a feud with the McMahon family. On the January 19 episode of ''Raw'', Orton [[Professional wrestling attacks#Punt|punted]] McMahon in the head, after he had tried to fire Orton from the company for previous comments made about Stephanie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090119/|title=Raw results \u2013 January 19, 2009|date=January 19, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=April 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401175744/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090119/|archivedate=April 1, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The following week, Shane returned to television and attacked Orton for his actions, turning face in the process for the first time since 2006. On the February 2 episode of ''Raw'', it was revealed that Orton challenged Shane to a No Holds Barred match at [[No Way Out (2009)|No Way Out]], to which he accepted,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/results/|title=Blistering Son|date=February 2, 2009|last=Adkins|first=Greg|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> but was defeated by Orton in the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/nowayout/matches/9274736/results/|title=Results: Legacy of Brutality|last=Sitterson|first=Aubrey|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=February 15, 2009}}</ref> The following night on ''Raw'', Shane challenged Orton to an unsanctioned match for that episode's main event. The match ended with Orton punting Shane in the head, as well as performing an ''[[Cutter (professional wrestling)#Jumping cutter|RKO]]'' on Stephanie McMahon.<ref name=\"February 16, 2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090216/|title=Raw results \u2013 February 16, 2009|date=February 16, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|accessdate=April 13, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408212424/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/raw/_090216/|archivedate=April 8, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nShane returned on the March 30 episode of ''Raw'', alongside Triple H and his father Vince McMahon, to confront and attack [[The Legacy (professional wrestling)|The Legacy]] (Randy Orton, [[Ted DiBiase Jr.|Ted DiBiase]], and [[Cody Rhodes]]). On the April 6 episode of ''Raw'', it was announced that Shane would compete in a [[Professional wrestling tag team match types#Multiple man teamed matches|six-man tag team match]] against The Legacy at [[Backlash (2009)|Backlash]] alongside Triple H and [[Dave Batista|Batista]], the latter of whom had returned from injury, where the stipulation was that if any member of Orton's team pinned any member of Triple H's team, Orton would win Triple H's WWE Championship; however, if any member of Orton's team was counted out or disqualified, Triple H would retain the title.<ref name=\"April 25, 2009\">{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/archive/04062009/|title=Results:Bringing in the big guns|first=Aubrey|last=Sitterson|date=April 6, 2009 |accessdate=April 25, 2009}}</ref> On the May 4 episode of ''Raw'', Shane's character suffered a broken leg and ankle at the hands of Orton and Legacy as a way to write him out of the story. In October 2009, Shane announced his resignation from WWE which went into effect at the end of the year.\n\n=== Return to WWE ===\n\n==== Commissioner of SmackDown Live (2016\u20132017) ====\nOn the February 22, 2016 episode of ''Raw'', Shane returned to WWE as a face for the first time in nearly seven years, interrupting his sister, [[Stephanie McMahon]], receiving the \"[[Vincent J. McMahon]] Legacy of Excellence\" Award from their father, [[Vince McMahon]]. Shane announced that the reason he had returned was that he wanted control of ''Raw'', leading to Vince placing Shane in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match at [[WrestleMania 32]] against [[The Undertaker]], adding the stipulation that Shane would get control of ''Raw'' and Undertaker would no longer be a participant in Future Wrestlemania's if he wins the match.<ref name=\"Raw2222016\">{{cite web|last1=Tedesco|first1=Mike|title=WWE RAW Results - 2/22/16 (Live results from Detroit)|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-wrestling-results/wwe-raw-results/57868-wwe-raw-results-2-22-16-live-results-from-detroit|website=wrestleview.com|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref> At WrestleMania, Shane attempted a Leap of Faith off the top of the cell but Undertaker moved out of the way and Shane fell through an announce table. Shane was defeated by Undertaker soon after.\n[[File:Shane McMahon Raw 2016.jpg|thumb|upright|McMahon during a [[WWE Raw|Raw]] show in April 2016]]\nDespite losing at WrestleMania, Shane controlled ''Raw'' for a month, firstly by his father, Vince, on the ''Raw'' after WrestleMania, then for the following three weeks after \"popular demand on social media\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wortman|first1=James|title=Shane McMahon will return to run Raw for the third consecutive week|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/raw/2016-04-18/article/might-shane-mcmahon-run-his-third-consecutive-raw|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref> This led to Stephanie confronting Shane, telling him that their father will decide who will control ''Raw'' at [[Payback (2016)|Payback]], where Vince announced that both Shane and Stephanie would be Co-general managers and have joint control of WWE.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Clapp|first1=John|title=Mr. McMahon will announce who controls Raw at WWE Payback|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwepayback/2016/article/mr-mcmahon-announce-who-controls-raw|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Meltzer|first1=Dave|authorlink1=Dave Meltzer|title=WWE Payback live results: Roman Reigns vs. AJ Styles; Kevin Owens vs. Sami Zayn|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/wwe-news/wwe-payback-live-results-roman-reigns-vs-aj-styles-kevin-owens-vs-sami-zayn-212001|website=f4wonline.com|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pruett|first1=Will|title=Pruett's Pause: WWE Payback 2016|url=http://prowrestling.net/site/2016/05/02/pruetts-pause-wwe-payback-2016-a-new-era-begins-with-the-same-tired-playbook-run-ins-galore-a-montreal-finish-and-dueling-mcmahons/|website=prowrestling.net|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July, after the announcement of the return of the [[WWE brand extension|brand extension]] with ''[[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]]'' moving to Tuesday and airing live weekly, Vince appointed Shane as the storyline commissioner of the SmackDown brand and Stephanie as the commissioner of Raw before tasking them to name a general manager for their respective shows. Shane appointed [[Daniel Bryan]] as the general manager of ''SmackDown''. At [[SummerSlam (2016)|SummerSlam]] on August 21, [[Brock Lesnar]] won his match against [[Randy Orton]] by [[technical knockout]] and continued to assault Orton as he was being tended to. Shane then confronted Lesnar, which resulted in Shane being attacked by Lesnar with a F-5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/wwe/story/brock-lesnar-bloodies-randy-orton-f5s-shane-mcmahon-at-summerslam-082116|title=Brock Lesnar F5's Shane McMahon at Summerslam|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> On the November 8 episode of ''SmackDown'', Shane agreed to replace an injured [[Baron Corbin]] in the traditional [[Survivor Series#Survivor Series matches|Survivor Series tag team elimination match]] between the two brands. At [[Survivor Series (2016)|Survivor Series]], Team SmackDown defeated Team Raw. McMahon suffered a legitimate concussion following a spear from [[Roman Reigns]], resulting in his elimination. In December, McMahon would take over host duties for ''Talking Smack'' with Daniel Bryan taking time off for family reasons.\n\nOn the February 21, 2017 episode of ''SmackDown'', after [[A.J. Styles|AJ Styles]] and [[Luke Harper]] simultaneously eliminated each other in a number one contenders battle royal as the final two entrants, McMahon made a singles match between the two for the February 28 episode of ''SmackDown'' with the winner going on to face [[Bray Wyatt]] for the WWE Championship at [[WrestleMania 33]]. Styles would originally go on to win the match before McMahon would restart the contest due to Harper having his foot on the rope during the pinfall. After McMahon accidentally distracted Harper, Styles would capitalise and pin Harper once again. That same week, after Randy Orton turned on Wyatt and cashed in his Royal Rumble winning opportunity, McMahon would go on to book a number one contender's match and the now even more infuriated Styles lost to Orton on the March 7 episode of ''SmackDown''. After losing the match, Styles would confront McMahon in the Gorilla position with things getting physical between the pair. The following week, Styles attacked McMahon inside the parking lot, which caused McMahon to be busted open and suffer a storyline concussion. Due to this, Styles was (kayfabe) \"fired\" from SmackDown. However, as McMahon was about to leave, he went back to the arena and announced that he will face Styles at WrestleMania 33. On April 2, at WrestleMania 33, McMahon lost to AJ Styles in a singles match. On April 4, the first episode of ''SmackDown'' after WrestleMania, McMahon and Styles shook hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ewrestling.com/article/aj-styles-teases-babyface-turn-post-wrestlemania-33-edition-sd-live|title=AJ Styles Teases Babyface Turn At Post-WrestleMania 33 Edition Of SD! Live {{!}} EWrestling|website=ewrestling.com|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\n==== Feud with Kevin Owens and Sami Zayn (2017\u20132018) ====\nOn the August 1 episode of ''SmackDown'', McMahon had a serious argument with [[Kevin Owens]] due to losing to AJ Styles for the [[WWE United States Championship|United States Championship]]. Owens demanded a competent referee, so Daniel Bryan chose McMahon to become the special guest referee. The following week on ''SmackDown'', McMahon was accidentally attacked by Styles during a brawl between Styles and Owens. Following the incident, on the August 15 episode of ''SmackDown'', McMahon warned Styles that if he puts his hands on him, he will put his hands on Styles. The warning later came to Owens after he accidentally attacked McMahon. At [[SummerSlam (2017)|SummerSlam]], McMahon was about to count the pin and declare Owens the winner, however after seeing Styles' foot on the bottom rope, McMahon continued the match. A frustrated Owens pushed McMahon, causing Shane to push him back. This caused a distraction for Styles to win back the United States Championship. On the August 22 episode of ''SmackDown'', McMahon allowed a rematch between Styles and Owens. During the match. Shane made himself referee after seeing the poor officiating from guest referee Baron Corbin, which caused a confrontation from Owens. This allowed Styles to take advantage and pin Owens to retain the championship. On the September 5 episode of ''SmackDown'', after a brief confrontation with [[Kevin Owens]], McMahon proceeded to beat down Owens after warning him not to talk about his family. Soon after, [[Daniel Bryan]] then came out to announce that Shane had been \"suspended indefinitely\" by [[Vince McMahon]], who would be returning to ''Smackdown Live'' next week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/2017-09-05/article/shane-mcmahon-suspended-as-smackdown-live-commissioner|title=Shane McMahon suspended indefinitely|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=5 September 2017}}</ref> On the September 12 episode of ''SmackDown'', CEO and Chairman of WWE, [[Vince McMahon]] announced that Shane will be facing [[Kevin Owens]] at [[Hell in a Cell (2017)|Hell in a Cell]], in a [[Hell in a Cell match]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Benigno|first1=Anthony|title=Shane McMahon vs. Kevin Owens (Hell in a Cell Match)|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/hellinacell/2017/shane-mcmahon-vs-kevin-owens-hell-in-a-cell-match|work=WWE|accessdate=September 12, 2017}}</ref> In McMahon's first pay-per-view main event since 2001, Owens won after being saved by [[Sami Zayn]] from McMahon's Leap of Faith from the top of the Cell to the announcer's table, then was dragged by Zayn to pin McMahon.\n\nOn the 23 October episode of ''Raw'', Shane McMahon fired the first shot in the build of the Smackdown vs Raw feud for [[Survivor Series (2017)|Survivor Series]] when he appeared with most of the ''SmackDown'' roster to attack the Raw roster, after initially being friendly with [[Kurt Angle]] earlier on in the same night. They proceeded to beat up wrestlers part of the ''Raw'' roster and bring Angle back to the ring. Then, Shane told Angle to bring his [[gold medal]] and the remains of the roster to Survivor Series and that at Survivor Series, they will finish what they started.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wrestlinginc.com/wi/news/2017/1023/633372/big-spoilers-on-john-cena-wwe-survivor-series-role/|title=Big Spoilers On John Cena's WWE Survivor Series Role, RAW Vs. SmackDown Matches, Tonight's RAW, More - WrestlingInc.com|work=WrestlingInc.com|access-date=2018-06-15|language=en}}</ref> However, several weeks later, on the November 14th edition of ''SmackDown'', during the main event between The New Day vs Kevin Owens and Sami Zayn, The Shield announced their presence and came down to the ring to face The New Day in payback for The New Day's distraction on the November 6th episode of ''Raw'' costing [[Seth Rollins]] and [[Dean Ambrose]] the [[WWE Raw Tag Team Championship]]. Worse was to come, as when [[The Usos]] tried to help, they were attacked by Cesaro and Sheamus, the Raw Women locker room attacked the SmackDown Women' locker room, and when the rest of the SmackDown male roster came down with Shane to the ring to help, they were attacked in turn by the rest of the Raw male roster, including Angle and Braun Strowman. Shane was given two triple powerbombs by The Shield, and an Angle Slam by Angle, as retribution for the trouble the ''SmackDown'' roster pulled on ''Raw'' the last couple of weeks, and to prove that come the pay-per-view, Team Raw would be victorious over Team SmackDown. At Survivor Series, Shane was the last man to be eliminated by Triple H, meaning Team SmackDown lost.\n[[File:ShaneMcMahon WM34 crop.jpg|thumb|upright|McMahon at [[WrestleMania 34]]]]\nOn March 11, 2018 at [[Fastlane (2018)|Fastlane]], Shane McMahon pulled the referee out of the ring when Kevin Owens covered Dolph Ziggler and pulled Sami Zayn out of the ring when he covered Kevin Owens. On the March 13 episode of SmackDown Live, Shane McMahon announced his indefinite leave of absence as SmackDown's commissioner. Kevin Owens and Sami Zayn then proceeded to attack Shane McMahon in the ring and behind the entrance. Shane (kayfabe) suffered laryngeal contusion, trapezius and rhomboid strains. He was then taken to a local medical facility. On March 26, 2018, WWE.com reported that Shane legitimately had acute diverticulitis while resting with his family in the Caribbean on March 14, and was hospitalized in Antigua for a few days before he was moved to a hospital in New York where doctors also found that Shane has an umbilical hernia that requires surgery once the infection is eradicated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/smackdown/article/shane-mcmahon-hospitalized|title=Shane McMahon hospitalized with diverticulitis|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> McMahon posted the below message to his [[Instagram]] account: \"Thank you everyone for the get well wishes. It truly helps. I'm healing up, and I have the best medicine in the world with me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.instagram.com/p/Bg1Q1swh2MG/|title= Shane McMahon (@shanemcmahonwwe)|publisher= [[Instagram]]}}</ref>\nIt was later announced that Shane would team up with [[Daniel Bryan]] against Owens and Zayn at [[WrestleMania 34]]. Shane returned on the April 3 episode of ''SmackDown Live'', to address his WrestleMania match, saying that Owens and Zayn would never be seen on a Smackdown Live arena again. At the event, Bryan and Shane defeated Zayn and Owens.\n\nHe then competed at the [[WWE Greatest Royal Rumble|Greatest Royal Rumble]], where he entered the namesake match at #47 before being eliminated after getting chokeslammed off the top rope through a table by [[Braun Strowman]]. Then, he took time off to heal from the injuries he suffered two months prior, returning on the [[SmackDown 1000|1000th edition of ''SmackDown'']] on October 16 alongside [[Stephanie McMahon]] and [[Vince McMahon]] on the ''Truth TV'' segment hosted by [[Ron Killings|R-Truth]] and [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]]. Following [[TLC: Tables, Ladders & Chairs (2018)|TLC: Tables, Ladders, & Chairs]] in December, The McMahon Family (Vince, Stephanie, Shane, and Triple H) appeared on ''Raw'' and announced that they would be running both Raw and SmackDown as a group with no general managers.\n\n==== Best in the World (2018\u20132019) ====\nAt the [[Crown Jewel (2018)|Crown Jewel]] event in November, he replaced [[The Miz]] after the latter suffered a (kayfabe) injury in the finals of the [[WWE World Cup]], and won by defeating [[Dolph Ziggler]] [[glossary of professional wrestling terms#Squash|in under three minutes]], winning the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/wwe-smackdown-results-recap-grades-wrestlemania-season-comes-to-an-eventful-conclusion/|title=WWE SmackDown results, recap, grades: WrestleMania season comes to an eventful conclusion|website=CBSSports.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> The Miz then began a pursuit to form a tag team with Shane, who finally agreed, and the two faced SmackDown Tag Team Champions [[Cesaro and Sheamus|The Bar]] ([[Cesaro (wrestler)|Cesaro]] and [[Sheamus]]) at the [[Royal Rumble (2019)|Royal Rumble]] pay-per-view, winning the titles. At [[Elimination Chamber (2019)|Elimination Chamber]] the following month, however, they lost the titles to [[The Usos]] (Jey Uso and Jimmy Uso),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2819445-the-usos-stun-miz-shane-mcmahon-win-tag-team-title-at-wwe-elimination-chamber|title=The Usos Stun Miz, Shane McMahon, Win Tag Team Title at WWE Elimination Chamber|last=Chiari|first=Mike|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref> and failed to regain them at [[Fastlane (2019)|Fastlane]], after which, McMahon attacked The Miz and taunted Miz's father, turning [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] for the first time since 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2822637-video-shane-mcmahon-turns-on-miz-after-losing-to-the-usos-at-wwe-fastlane-2019|title=Video: Shane McMahon Attacks Miz After Losing to The Usos at WWE Fastlane 2019|last=Chiari|first=Mike|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2019-03-10}}</ref> McMahon then heelishly began proclaiming himself as the \"Best in the World\" and scheduled a match between himself and Miz at [[WrestleMania 35]], which Miz requested to be a Falls Count Anywhere match, and Shane agreed. At WrestleMania, McMahon narrowly defeated Miz after being [[superplex]]ed off a 15-foot platform and landing on top of Miz for the 3 count.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/04/07/wwe-wrestlemania-35-results-shane-mcmahon-defeats-the-miz-in-stunt-filled-brawl/|title=WWE WrestleMania 35 Results: Shane McMahon Defeats The Miz In Stunt-Filled Brawl|first=Alfred|last=Konuwa|website=Forbes}}</ref> On the April 29 edition of ''Raw'', McMahon helped [[Bobby Lashley]] defeat Miz, who was [[2019 WWE Superstar Shake-up|drafted to Raw]], and then McMahon attacked Miz. Later that night, Miz challenged McMahon to a Steel Cage Match at [[Money in the Bank (2019)|Money in the Bank]], which Shane accepted.\n\nWhile simultaneously feuding with Miz on Raw, over on SmackDown, [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]] and [[Roman Reigns]] were drafted to the brand. Shane's father Vince introduced Elias as SmackDown's biggest acquisition on the April 16 episode of ''SmackDown''. The two were confronted by Reigns, who attacked Elias and attacked Vince with the Superman Punch. The following week, Shane called out Reigns for a fight for attacking his father, but Reigns was attacked from behind by Elias, who was assisted by Shane, forming an alliance between Elias and Shane. Shane then forced Reigns to face The B-Team ([[Bo Dallas]] and [[Curtis Axel]]) in a handicap match with Elias as the special referee enforcer that Reigns won. The following week on ''SmackDown'', Shane teamed with Elias, Daniel Bryan, and [[Erick Rowan|Rowan]] in a seven-man handicap match and defeated the team of  Reigns and The Usos. At Money In The Bank, Shane once again defeated The Miz this time by escaping the cage ending their feud. The following night on RAW, Shane confronted Roman Reigns with Reigns challenging Shane to a match at Super ShowDown which Shane accepted. At [[Super ShowDown (2019)|Super ShowDown]], Shane defeated Roman Reigns after interference from [[Drew McIntyre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-super-showdown/2019/roman-reigns-vs-shane-mcmahon-results|title=WWE Super ShowDown Results: \"The Best in the World\" Shane McMahon def. Roman Reigns|accessdate=June 7, 2019|author=James Wortman|publisher=[[WWE]].com}}</ref> Shane and McIntyre lost to Reigns and [[The Undertaker]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types|No Holds Barred]] tag team match at [[Extreme Rules (2019)|Extreme Rules]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Benigno|first=Anthony|title=The Undertaker & Roman Reigns def. Shane McMahon & Drew McIntyre (No Holds Barred Match)|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/extremerules/extreme-rules-2019/undertaker-roman-reigns-vs-shane-mcmahon-drew-mcintyre-results|work=WWE|accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing this, McMahon re-ignited his feud with [[Kevin Owens]], after Owens stated his distaste in McMahon's constant dominance on television and began to hit him with the ''Stunner'' on countless occasions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/videos/kevin-owens-rants-against-shane-mcmahon-smackdown-live-july-9-2019|title=Kevin Owens tears into Shane McMahon in shocking rant|via=www.wwe.com}}</ref> McMahon lost to Owens at [[SummerSlam (2019)|SummerSlam]] where had Owens lost he would have quit WWE. McMahon later replaced an injured Elias in a semi-final match against [[Chad Gable]] for the [[2019 King of the Ring]] tournament, and Owens was made the referee, and despite McMahon's promise to consider dropping a fine for Owens damaging expensive equipment, Owens allowed Gable to win, and Owens was hereby fired. However, Owens continued to appear on TV to issue legal threats, until October 4's [[WWE SmackDown's 20th Anniversary]] episode, where McMahon was \"fired\" after losing a ladder match against Owens.<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/10/04/wwe-friday-night-smackdown-results-shane-mcmahon-loses-to-kevin-owens-becomes-immediate-candidate-to-join-nxt/</ref>\n\n== Business career ==\nShane McMahon began working in WWE at age 15, starting in their warehouse, where he filled merchandise orders. McMahon was also a referee, producer, announcer, and eventually a wrestler on-screen, while also becoming WWE's Executive Vice President of Global Media behind the scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/shane-mcmahon}}</ref>\n\nOn October 21, 2006, [[Pride Fighting Championships]] held [[Pride 32]] at the [[Thomas & Mack Center]] in [[Paradise, Nevada]]. Shane was in attendance at the event,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.foxsports.com/blogs/FOXSportsMMA/2006/10/25/Showbiz_and_MMA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106095647/http://community.foxsports.com/blogs/FOXSportsMMA/2006/10/25/Showbiz_and_MMA|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 6, 2006|title=Showbiz and MMA \u2013 Dave Doyle's FOXSports.com MMA Blog \u2013 FOX Sports Blogs|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref> resulting in speculation that WWE could be considering promoting MMA events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightopinion.com/2006/10/22/is-wwe-getting-into-the-mma-business/|title=FightOpinion.com \u2013 Your Global Connection to the Fight Industry|accessdate= May 25, 2007}}</ref> On November 17, WWE and [[Dream Stage Entertainment]] officials, the parent company of Pride Fighting Championships, had a meeting at WWE global headquarters in [[Stamford, Connecticut]]. The meeting focused on the possibility of the two groups doing some form of business together in the future.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/archive/34401241|title=Update on PRIDE \u2013 WWE meeting|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref> Yet on March 27, 2007, [[Nobuyuki Sakakibara]], president of DSE, announced that [[Station Casinos]], Inc. magnate Lorenzo Fertitta, also one of the co-owners of Zuffa, the parent company of the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]], had made a deal to acquire all the assets of Pride FC from DSE after [[Pride 34]] in a deal worth about US$70 million, thereby ceasing any prospective business between Pride and WWE.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.pridefc.com/pride2005/index.php?mainpage=news&news_id=1035|title=\"Japanese Magazine \"Kamipro\" Interview with DSE President Nobuyuki Sakakibara|accessdate=May 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nLater in November, McMahon and WWE Canada President [[Carl De Marco]] traveled to South America to finalize a major TV deal in [[Brazil]], which allowed their television station to air ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'' and ''[[WWE Friday Night SmackDown|SmackDown]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2007_/articles/1196108928.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128223206/http://www.lordsofpain.net/news/2007_/articles/1196108928.php|url-status=dead|title=Sid Vicious Talking With Vince McMahon; Shane McMahon Update, House Show Draws Lackluster Crowd|archivedate=November 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2008, McMahon finalized another major TV deal, this time in Mexico, which allowed WWE programming to air on Mexico's two biggest television networks, ''Raw'' on [[Televisa]] and ''SmackDown'' on [[TV Azteca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestling.net/artman/publish/WWE/article1002737.shtml|title=WWE to announce another TV deal|accessdate=August 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, 2009, WWE published a statement from Shane McMahon announcing his resignation from his position as WWE's Executive Vice President of Global Media,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/shanemcmahonresigns|title=Shane McMahon resigns|accessdate=October 16, 2009|publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment, Inc.}}</ref> and also issued an official press release stating that the resignation was tendered effective January 1, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/news/shanemcmahontodepartWWE|title=Shane McMahon to depart WWE|accessdate=October 16, 2009|publisher=World Wrestling Entertainment, Inc.}}</ref> No specific reason was given for the resignation. McMahon stated in the WWE press release, \"Having been associated with this organization for the majority of my life, I feel this is the opportune time in my career to pursue outside ventures.\" thus ending his 20-year stint with the company on January 1, 2010. McMahon's resignation left only two original members of the McMahon family active within the company; his father Vince, and his sister, Stephanie.\n\nOn August 3, 2010, McMahon became the CEO of China Broadband Inc., a provider of cable broadband services, as well as other digital and analog related services, in [[Shandong]] province of [[China]]. The company is based in [[Boulder County, Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1280883897|title=Shane McMahon new CEO of China Broadband Inc|publisher=Wrestle View|accessdate=August 5, 2010|date=August 3, 2010|first=Adam|last=Martin|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120511065745/http://www.wrestleview.com/viewnews.php?id=1280883897|archivedate=May 11, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Also in 2010, McMahon became the CEO of You On Demand, the first [[video-on-demand]] and pay-per-view service in China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/18/business/la-fi-ct-shane-mcmahon-20110618|title=Shane McMahon looking to make his mark with China venture|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2011|date=June 18, 2011|first=Joe|last=Flint}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20130217/MEDIA_ENTERTAINMENT/302179989/shane-mcmahon-goes-to-china|title=Shane McMahon goes to China|publisher=crainsnewyork.com|accessdate=February 17, 2013|date=February 17, 2013|first=Chris|last=Bragg}}</ref> In 2013, McMahon stepped down as CEO of You On Demand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/wwe/shane-mcmahon-resigns-as-ceo-of-you-on-demand/|title=Shane McMahon resigns as CEO of 'YOU on Demand'|date=2013-09-05|website=www.sportskeeda.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref> McMahon remains Executive Vice Chairman of the Board of Directors of the company, which has undergone several name changes since that time, including Wecast Holdings Inc., Seven Stars Cloud Group, Inc., and ultimately, Ideanomics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=33570440|title=Seven Stars Cloud Group, Inc.: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> The company is headquartered in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://data.intrinio.com/company/SSC}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2011, McMahon sits on the Board of Directors for International Sports Management representing talent such as [[Ernie Els]] and (previously<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/golf/sport/story/117175.html|title=McIlroy parts company with Chandler and ISM|accessdate=June 14, 2014|publisher=ESPN Sports Media Ltd.}}</ref>) [[Rory McIlroy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rajah.com/base/node/22531|title=Shane McMahon Update, Jericho Makes Reality Love Connection, WM28|publisher=Rajah.com|accessdate=April 12, 2011|date=April 12, 2011|first=Michael|last=Bluth}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon is also a part owner of the [[Indian Larry]] Motorcycle Shop in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|NY]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.inkedmag.com/articles/question-everything|title=Question everything - Inked Magazine}}</ref>\n\nShane McMahon still remains a minority owner of WWE,<ref>{Cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/wwe/who-is-the-real-owner-of-wwe}}</ref> owning 2 percent of the company's shares.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/player/shane-mcmahon}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nMcMahon is married to Marissa Mazzola.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oliver|first=Greg|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2006/07/20/1694331.html|title=Shane McMahon aiming for respect|date=|accessdate=July 7, 2018|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> They have three sons.<ref name=\"WM32 Sons\"/> His sons appeared at [[WrestleMania 32]], accompanying him to the ring in his match against [[The Undertaker]]; they have also been seen in the crowd for some of his more recent matches.<ref name=\"WM32 Sons\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/wwe/story/wwe-wrestlemania-32-shane-mcmahon-entrance-with-his-three-sons-040316|title=Shane McMahon makes WrestleMania 32 entrance with his three sons|last=Werner|first=Barry|website=[[Foxsports.com]]|date=April 3, 2016|access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMcMahon usually wears baseball jerseys for his matches, with the front saying \"Shane O Mac\" and the back reserved for \"McMahon\", the name of the pay-per-view in which he's participating, or some other phrase relating to the match and/or his opponent. When his father, [[Vince McMahon|Vince]], was interviewed in ''[[Playboy]]'', he mentioned that although Shane is [[right-handed]], he often throws left-handed punches. McMahon's football jersey number was 61,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/pictures/s/shanemcmahon/01.jpg|title=Shane McMahon's football jersey number|accessdate= August 6, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> the same as his father.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/pictures/f/football/vince.jpg|title=Shane and Vince's football jersey number|accessdate= August 6, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> On July 19, 2017, McMahon was involved in a helicopter crash, but was relatively unharmed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tmz.com/2017/07/19/wwe-shane-mcmahon-helicopter-crash-atlantic-ocean/|title=WWE'S SHANE MCMAHONHELICOPTER CRASHES... Escapes Uninjured|author=TMZ staff|work=[[TMZ]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Other media ==\nIn September 2006, he was named one of ''[[Details (magazine)|Detail]]'' magazine's \"50 Most Powerful Men Under 42\" in the annual \"power issue\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://men.style.com/details/features/full?id=content_4990&pageNum=17|title=The Power 50: Details Article on men.style.com|accessdate=July 17, 2007|work=[[Details (magazine)|Detail Magazine]]|date=October 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927224324/http://men.style.com/details/features/full?id=content_4990&pageNum=17|archivedate=September 27, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Filmography ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Feature films\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Note\n|-\n|1999 || ''[[Beyond the Mat|Beyond The Mat]]'' || Himself || [[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n|-\n|2002 || ''[[Rollerball (2002 film)|Rollerball]]'' || American Media Mogul ||Cameo appearance\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Television\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Note\n|-\n|2019 || ''[[NCIS: Los Angeles]]'' || [[United States Army Criminal Investigation Command|US Army CID]] Special Agent Steve Evans || 2 episodes\n|}\n\n=== Video games ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year 